{[%evp 0,30,18,14,27,11,38,44,40,-17,10,-12,2,2,2,-29,-32,-26,-40,-8,-8,-49,-36,-47,-28,-18,-18,-18,-30,-23,-22,-52,-26]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Qa4+ {We have seen a lot of this idea in the practice. The latest theory shows that Black has a couple of ways for obtaining a very promising position.} Bd7 5. Qb3 (5. Qd1 {might be objectively the best, although it is not ambitious at all.} Bc8 {The simplest, Black is simply inviting White to deviate.} ({Untimely is} 5... dxc4 $6 6. e4 c5 7. d5 $16) ({However, both} 5... Bc6) ({and} 5... c6 {are fully playable}) 6. Qa4+ $11) 5... c5 $1 {A relatively rare move, but in my opinion, it is the best one. White must already tread extremely carefully.} ({The most frequently played move is} 5... dxc4 {, the resulting positions after the principled 6.?:c4 ?e6! will be the subject of Chapter 11.}) ({Another interesting option here for Black is} 5... Nc6 $5 {[%cal Gc6a5]} 6. Nf3 ({Or} 6. e3 Na5) 6... Na5 7. Qc2 c6 $1 {The best way to handle the pressure in the centre.} ({The alternatives are slightly worse -} 7... Nxc4 8. Nxd5) ({or} 7... Bf5 8. Qa4+) 8. e4 {Sacrificing a pawn and hoping to get some initiative.} (8. cxd5 {is pretty safe, but it is also not very demanding -} cxd5 9. Bf4 Bg7 10. e3 Rc8 11. Bd3 Nh5 $11 {and Black has no problems}) 8... Nxc4 9. e5 (9. exd5 $143 $6 Nd6 $15) 9... Nh5 10. Bd3 Ng7 11. b3 Nb6 $132 {The game is very complicated, but Black's chances are not worse.}) 6. Nxd5 {The only decent move.} (6. dxc5 $6 {looks very suspicious for White after} d4 7. Nd5 ({or} 7. Nb5 Nc6 $17) 7... Na6 {[%cal Ga6c5]} 8. Nxf6+ ({Black is winning after} 8. Qxb7 $2 Nxd5 9. c6 Bc8 $1 10. Qxa8 Ndb4 $19) 8... exf6 9. Qxb7 Nxc5 10. Qd5 Ne6 11. Nf3 Rb8 $17 {[%csl Re1]}) ({Of course not} 6. Qxb7 $2 {in the view of} Bc6 $19 {[%cal Gc5d4]}) 6... cxd4 7. e3 ({Once again} 7. Qxb7 $6 {is not a good idea because of} Bc6 {, when the impulsive} 8. Nc7+ $2 Kd7 $19 {just drops material.}) 7... Nc6 8. Nf3 Bg7 9. Be2 O-O {White is already behind in development and he is the one who should fight for equality, for example} 10. exd4 Nxd5 11. cxd5 Nxd4 12. Nxd4 Bxd4 13. O-O Qb6 {The simplest plan.} 14. Qxb6 axb6 {This idea to open the a-file, whilst holding ?d4 on the big diagonal, yields more options to Black.} ({Alternatively, about equal is} 14... Bxb6 15. Bf4 Rac8 $11) 15. Bf3 b5 $15 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Ga8a1] I believe Black has a bit more comfortable position, and definitely slightly better chances.} *

