s winning after} Nc6 $1 11. Nxa8 Qa5+ 12. Bd2 Nxd2 13. Nxd2 Nxd4 $19 {[%csl Re1] due to White's king misfortunate position in the center}) 10... Nc6 $15 {[%cal Gc6b4] Black has an easy game.}) 8... c6 {[%cal Gb7b5] One of the main moves and my personal favourite at the same time. Black's plan is simple - to push b7-b5 and then even c6-c5 as soon as possible.} ({Very interesting is} 8... Na6 $5 9. e4 c5 10. e5 Nh5 11. Be3 $13 {with extremely sharp position.}) 9. e4 {The only critical move.} (9. e3 {is too modest and Black has an excellent game by simple means -} Qb6 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Gb6b2]} ({other possibilities are} 9... b5) ({or} 9... Be6) 10. Qb3 c5 $15 {[%cal Gb8c6] and Black is doing great.}) 9... b5 {Here White has a large choice where to put his queen.} 10. Qb3 {is probably the best. The rest of the possible moves are risky for White:} (10. Qd3 c5 $1 {Black is definitely seizing the initiative.} 11. dxc5 (11. e5 $143 $6 Nh5 12. Be3 b4 13. Ne4 Bf5 14. dxc5 Nc6 $17 {[%csl Re5] White's position is already about to collapse}) 11... b4 $1 {The best move in my opinion.} ({Plausible alternatives are both} 11... Na6) ({and} 11... Bc6) 12. Nd5 ({too passive is} 12. Nd1 $6 Bc6 $15) 12... Nxd5 13. exd5 Bxb2 14. Be5 $1 {The only move for White to stay in the game.} Bxe5 {Simple play, indeed, taking the rook is too risky.} 15. Nxe5 Qa5 $132 {[%cal Gb4b3,Ga5c5] Black is fine.}) (10. Qe2 Bg4 $1 {Undoubtedly the best move, attacking the central d4-pawn is very typical. Other possibilities are} (10... Qa5) ({or} 10... b4) 11. Rd1 ({strategically flawed is} 11. e5 Nd5 12. Nxd5 Qxd5 13. Be3 f6 $15 {and White has problems with developing his pieces}) 11... b4 12. Na4 Qa5 13. b3 Nbd7 14. h3 ({Or} 14. Qc2 Rfc8 $15 {[%cal Gc6c5]}) 14... Bxf3 15. gxf3 e5 16. dxe5 Nxe5 17. Bg2 Nh5 18. Be3 g5 $1 $15 {[%cal Gh5f4] Black is definitely better. Now} 19. Bxg5 $2 {is disastrous because of} Nd3+ $1 20. Qxd3 Qxg5 $19 {[%csl Re1][%cal Gh5f4] with full control over the dark squares.}) 10... c5 $1 {This main theoretical move is most probably the best one.} ({The other reasonable options are} 10... Qa5 {and 10...a5.}) 11. dxc5 (11. Bxb5 $6 {might be close to equality, nevertheless, it looks suspicious for White.} cxd4 12. Nxd4 Nh5 $1 {Black is apparently playing for a win.} ({An easy way to equalize is} 12... Nxe4 13. Nxe4 Bxd4 14. O-O Qb6 15. Bxd7 Nxd7 $11) 13. Nde2 {The only move.} (13. Be3 $2 {loses to} Bxd4 $1 14. Bxd4 Bxb5 15. Nxb5 a6 $19 {[%csl Rb5,Rd4] and White will be a piece down}) 13... Nxf4 14. Nxf4 Qa5 {Black has a very nice game and is still fighting for the advantage.} 15. Bxd7 ({Or} 15. Nfe2 Rc8) 15... Nxd7 16. O-O Rab8 17. Qc2 Rxb2 {I believe it is difficult for Black to win here, but in any case, his position is very comfortable.} 18. Qxb2 Bxc3 19. Qe2 Bxa1 20. Rxa1 Qe5 21. Rd1 Nf6 22. Nd5 $11) 11... Qa5 $1 {Both sides must be extremely accurate.} 12. Bd2 ({Of course,} 12. e5 $6 Ne4 $15 {is hardly recommendable.}) 12... b4 $1 {The forced sequence continues.} 13. Nd5 Nc6 $1 (13... Nxd5 $6 14. exd5 Qxc5 15. Bxb4 $14) ({Even worse is} 13... Nxe4 $2 14. Bxb4 $16) 14. Bd3 {The best move, the alternatives are not good, for example:} (14. Nxb4 $2 {is just bad in the view of} Nxe4 15. Nxc6 Qxc5 $1 $17 {A very important intermediate move, which gives Black the advantage}) (14. Qc4 $2 {is also wrong because of} Be6 $1 15. Ng5 Rad8 $1 {Black has excellent attacking possibilities -} 16. Nxe6 fxe6 {and now:} 17. Nxf6+ (17. Nxb4 Rd4 $1 18. Qxe6+ Kh8 19. Nd3 ({Or} 19. Qxc6 Rxd2 $1 $19) 19... Nb4 $1 {A very nice move.} 20. Bxb4 Rxb4 $17 {Black is clearly dominating}) (17. Nf4 {loses to} Rxd2 $1 18. Kxd2 b3+ 19. Ke2 Ng4 $19 {[%csl Re2][%cal Gc6d4] and Black has too many threats}) 17... Bxf6 18. Qxe6+ ({or} 18. O-O-O Rxd2 $1 19. Rxd2 Bg5 $19 {and Black wins on the spot}) 18... Kg7 19. Qxc6 Rxd2 $1 {The big point, Black's attack is unstoppable.} 20. Kxd2 b3+ 21. Ke3 ({Or} 21. Ke2 Bxb2 $19) 21... Bg5+ 22. Kd3 Qd2+ 23. Kc4 Rb8 $19 {[%csl Rc4] Black has a decisive attack.}) (14. Nxf6+ {is the least evil, but White is still fighting for equality after} Bxf6 15. Bc4 ({or} 15. Rc1 {, when} Be6 16. Bc4 Bxc4 17. Rxc4 Qa6 $1 $15 {[%csl Re1][%cal Gc6a5] is still keeping the White's king in the center}) 15... Qxc5 16. Rc1 Qb6 17. Be3 Qb7 {[%cal Gc6a5] The threat is î ..a5.} 18. Qc2 Rac8 19. Qe2 Qb8 20. Ba6 (20. O-O $143 Bg4 $15) 20... Nd4 $1 {A beautiful move, which retains a small, but pleasant edge for Black.} 21. Rxc8 Nxf3+ 22. gxf3 Bxc8 23. Bxc8 Qxc8 24. O-O Qh3 $11 {It might be closer to equality, but it is only Black, who is playing on two results.}) 14... Be6 15. O-O (15. Ng5 $143 $6 {is met by} Bxd5 $1 16. exd5 Ne5 $15) 15... Rfd8 ({Of course not} 15... Qxc5 $2 16. Rac1 Qd6 17. Rxc6 $1 $18 {and White wins material.}) 16. Bc4 ({Harmless is} 16. Nxf6+ Bxf6 17. Bc4 {, when} Bxc4 18. Qxc4 Bxb2 19. Rab1 Qa3 $11 {looks balanced, perhaps White should do some work to equalize completely.}) 16... Nxe4 {Giving rise to an exciting skirmish.} 17. Nxe7+ Nxe7 18. Bxb4 Bxc4 19. Qxc4 Qa4 $1 {The key move.} 20. Rae1 (20. Qxe4 $2 {is a mistake, after} Nd5 21. a3 a5 {White is losing material, for example} 22. Rad1 Nf6 23. Rxd8+ Rxd8 $17) (20. b3 {is possible, leading to approximately equal endgame after} Qe8 $1 ({but not} 20... Qc6 $2 21. Rae1) 21. Qxe4 Bxa1 22. Rxa1 Nc6 23. Qxe8+ Rxe8 24. Bc3 Re2 $11) 20... a5 {The easiest way to equalize.} ({Perhaps Black can also rely on} 20... Nd2 21. Nxd2 Rd4 22. Qb3 Rxb4 23. Qxa4 Rxa4 24. Rxe7 Rc8 25. Ne4 Bxb2 $11 {, about equal.}) 21. Rxe4 ({Equivalent is} 21. Qxe4 axb4 22. Qxe7 Bxb2 23. Ne5 ({or} 23. Ng5 Rd7) 23... Bxe5 24. Qxe5 Qxa2 $11 {with inevitable draw.}) 21... Qxb4 22. Qxb4 axb4 23. Rxe7 Rxa2 24. c6 Rc8 $11 *

