b7) 10. Rd1 ({The alternatives are:} 10. Bd2 c5 11. dxc5 bxc5 12. Rac1 Nc6 $132 {[%cal Ga8b8] Black has very active pieces}) (10. Ne5 c5 $1 11. f4 Bb7 $1 {[%cal Gb8c6] I believe this is the best, it secures î ..c6.} ({In case of} 11... Ba6 {White has the promising idea} 12. Bf3 $5 ({Black is absolutely fine after} 12. Bxa6 Nxa6 13. Bd2 Nc7 $132) 12... Bxf1 13. Kxf1 $44 {[%csl Rd5] The game is very sharp, Black has problems to solve}) 12. dxc5 {There is nothing better, otherwise Black will simply realize his idea.} Nc6 $1 13. Bb5 ({Or} 13. cxb6 axb6 14. Nxc6 Bxc6 15. Bf3 Ne4 $44 {with excellent compensation for the pawn}) 13... Nxe5 $5 {I like very much this positional sacrifice of an exchange.} ({Black, if he wishes, can also go after the simple} 13... Re6 14. Bxc6 Bxc6 15. cxb6 axb6 $44) 14. Bxe8 Nxe8 ({less accurate is} 14... Qxe8 {in the view of} 15. fxe5 Qxe5 16. cxb6 Ng4 17. Rf4 Nxe3 18. Nb5 $1 {[%cal Gc1e3] with wild complications}) 15. fxe5 Bxe5 $44 {[%cal Gd8h4] Now it becomes clear that Black has obtained a very nice counterplay.} 16. h3 (16. Bd2 {is invites Black to force perpetual by} Qh4 17. g3 Bxg3 18. hxg3 Qxg3+ $11) 16... Ba6 $1 ({here} 16... Qh4 $6 {does not reach its purpose in because of} 17. Ne2) 17. Rf3 ({similar is} 17. Rd1 Bc4) 17... Bc4 18. Qc2 bxc5 {The game is still extremely complicated.} 19. b3 ({an exciting line goes on with} 19. e4 Bd4+ 20. Kh1 dxe4 21. Nxe4 Bd5 {[%csl Gd4,Gd5] and Black's bishops are dominating the board -} 22. Bg5 f6 23. Be3 Rc8 24. Rd1 f5 25. Bh6 Ng7 $132 {[%csl Gd4,Gd5]}) 19... Ba6 20. Bb2 d4 21. Ne4 ({or} 21. Na4 Rc8) 21... Rc8 {Black has every chance to fight for the advantage due to the active pieces.} 22. Qf2 f5 23. exd4 cxd4 24. Re1 Qd5 25. Ng3 ({the sample line} 25. Ng5 h6 26. Ne6 Qxe6 27. Bxd4 Bxd4 28. Rxe6 Bxf2+ 29. Rxf2 Bd3 30. Rxg6+ {is leading to an approximately equal ending}) 25... Ng7 26. Rxe5 {White must eliminate this powerful piece.} Qxe5 27. Bxd4 Rc1+ 28. Kh2 Qc7 {The fight can continue with} 29. Qe3 Rc2 30. Rf2 Bb7 31. Bxg7 Rxf2 32. Qxf2 Kxg7 33. Qxa7 f4 34. Qd4+ Kg8 35. Ne4 f3+ 36. g3 Qc2+ 37. Nf2 Qxa2 $11 {and a likely draw}) 10... Bb7 {It is already time to place the bishop here.} 11. Bd2 Nbd7 12. Be1 a5 $5 {I like this plan very much.} (12... c5 $143 13. a4 $5 a6 14. dxc5 Nxc5 15. Qa2 {and White's position is more comfortable}) 13. Rac1 c6 $11 {Black is fine.}) (5. b4 {A rare idea, but not without venom - White seizes space on the queenside but at the cost of postponing his development.} O-O {and now:} 6. Bb2 (6. Qb3 $6 {must be considered here as well. However, it is a bit pushy and provides conditions for starting a fierce counterattack like} a5 $1 7. b5 c5 $1 {- Black is ready to crush the opponent's centre.} 8. bxc6 ({or} 8. dxc5 Ne4 $17) 8... Nxc6 9. cxd5 a4 $1 {Yet another blow in the fight for the initiative -} 10. Qc4 Na5 11. Qxa4 ({or} 11. Qb5 Bd7 12. Qb1 Qc7 $17) 11... Nxd5 12. Nxd5 Qxd5 {and Black is at least equal after} 13. Qb5 Qxb5 14. Bxb5 Nb3 15. Rb1 Nxc1 16. Rxc1 Rxa2 $15) 6... Be6 $1 {Attacking the c4-pawn in order to clarify the pawn structure.} ({another interesting idea is} 6... Nc6 $5) 7. c5 ({in case of} 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. a3 a5 9. b5 c5 10. bxc6 Nxc6 $15 {[%csl Re1,Rf1,Rg1][%cal Ga8c8] Black is already better developed}) 7... Nc6 8. a3 ({after} 8. b5 Na5 9. Nf3 c6 10. bxc6 bxc6 11. Qa4 Rb8 $15 {[%cal Gb8b2,Gf6e4,Ga5c4] Black is the first to step on the b-file}) 8... Bg4 {[%cal Ge7e5]} 9. Be2 Bxe2 10. Ncxe2 (10. Ngxe2 $143 e5 $15) 10... e5 {The most natural move.} ({the preliminary} 10... b5 $5 {also deserves attention}) 11. dxe5 (11. b5 $143 $6 Na5 12. dxe5 Nc4 $1 13. Bd4 Ne4 14. Nf3 c6 $15 {[%cal Gd8a5] Black is enjoying fantastic squares for his knights}) 11... Ng4 12. Nf3 Ngxe5 13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14. Rb1 c6 15. O-O Qe7 $11 {and Black has a very comfortable play.}) (5. Nf3 {leads to the next Chapter 4.}) 5... Nxd5 6. Nxd5 {A part of White's slow positional system.} ({The alternatives are:} 6. Qb3 Nxc3 (6... Nb6 {is quite playable either}) 7. bxc3 c5 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Be2 Nc6 10. O-O Qc7 {This position is quite typical for Gruenfeld. I don't see any problems from Black's point of view, for example:} 11. Rd1 (11. Ba3 Be6 12. Qb5 (12. Qb2 b6 $11) 12... cxd4 13. cxd4 Rfd8 14. Rfc1 Rac8 $11) 11... Na5 12. Qa3 b6 13. e4 Bb7 14. Bd3 ({or} 14. d5 e6 $132) 14... e6 $11) (6. Bc4 Nb6 7. Bb3 c5 8. Nf3 O-O {transposes to the next Chapter 4.}) 6... Qxd5 7. Ne2 {[%cal Ge2c3] This is White's idea - the knight is hurrying to the c3-square in order to replace its colleague on it, chase the queen and complete the development of his kingside.} O-O 8. Nc3 Qd6 {One of the many good moves, such as} (8... Qd8) ({or} 8... Qd7) 9. Be2 c5 $5 {I prefer this direct approach.} ({Also possible is} 9... c6 10. O-O Nd7 {[%cal Ge7e5]}) ({or} 9... Na6 {[%cal Gc7c5]}) 10. d5 ({The alternative is to take the c5-pawn by} 10. Ne4 Qc7 (10... Qc6 $143 $6 11. d5) 11. Nxc5 e5 {It is clear that Black gets plenty of initiative in return for the pawn:} 12. O-O (12. Nb3 Rd8 13. O-O ({Or} 13. d5 e4 $132) 13... a5 {[%cal Ga5a4]} 14. a4 Nc6 15. d5 e4 $132 {looks problematic only for White}) 12... Rd8 $5 {Keeping more options to fight for the advantage.} ({another equalizer is} 12... exd4 13. exd4 Nc6) 13. Bd2 ({other options are} 13. Nd3 Nc6 $132) (13. Nb3 a5 14. a4 Nc6 15. d5 e4 $132) 13... exd4 14. Rc1 Nc6 {The easiest way to get a good game.} ({instead,} 14... dxe3 15. Ne6 Qd7 $13 {is very sharp}) 15. e4 Qe7 16. Re1 Ne5 17. Nd3 Bg4 18. f3 Be6 $11) 10... e6 11. e4 exd5 12. exd5 Re8 13. O-O Bf5 $1 {It is good to develop all the pieces.} (13... Nd7 $143 14. Be3 $14) 14. Be3 {The most natural place for the bishop, but Black has achieved a fine Benoni:} (14. Nb5 Qe5) (14. g4 Be4 $132 {looks risky for White}) (14. a4 Nd7 15. a5 (15. g4 Be4) (15. Be3 a6) 15... a6 $11) (14. Bg5 Nd7 15. Qd2 a6 16. a4 Ne5 17. Rfe1 c4 $15 {and Black is already slightly better in Krasenkow - Cheparinov, Tornelo INT, 2021.}) 14... Nd7 15. Qd2 (15. g4 $6 {is once again strongly met by} Be4) (15. Re1 a6 16. a4 Rac8 $11 {[%cal Gc5c4]}) 15... a6 16. a4 Ne5 17. a5 ({In case of} 17. Rfd1 c4 18. Bd4 {very strong is} b6 $1 $132 {for preventing a4-a5.}) 17... c4 {One of the possible ways to continue the game.} 18. Bf4 b5 19. axb6 Qxb6 $11 {Black is doing great, he is at least equal.} *

