{[%evp 0,36,20,20,23,5,42,44,51,42,46,44,22,10,27,4,5,19,16,-5,20,12,12,-5,-12,-4,22,16,16,16,3,7,47,-11,-11,-58,-33,-62,3]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. e3 {A similar idea to the one from the previous Chapter, but with Ng1 being developed on its most usual square.} O-O 6. Be2 {At some point this line was the favourite of Mamedyarov's.} (6. Bd2 {has been pioneered by very strong grandmasters as well.} c5 $1 {One of the most typical and natural moves in the Gruenfeld.} 7. dxc5 ({harmless is} 7. cxd5 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nxd5 $11) 7... Na6 $5 {The main move next to the natural 7... Nc6.} 8. cxd5 Nxc5 9. Bc4 Bf5 $1 {The best move order.} ({Many players prefer to include a6/a4 -} 9... a6 10. a4 Bf5 11. O-O Rc8 12. Be1 $14 {There is a small difference, which is slightly in White's favour}) (9... b6 $5 {[%cal Gc8b7] is yet another move, which is likely to equalize}) 10. O-O Rc8 11. Be1 {This is probably the best try for White.} (11. Nd4 Bd3 12. Bxd3 Nxd3 13. Qb1 Nc5 $1 {[%csl Rd5]} (13... Nb4 $143 $6 14. Ncb5 $1 {[%csl Ra7,Rb4]}) 14. b4 Ncd7 15. Rd1 Nb6 $11 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gf6d5] Black has no problems at all}) (11. Qe2 {The most frequently played move. Here Black equalizes by} Nfe4 $1 12. Rfd1 (12. Nd4 $143 $6 Nxd2 13. Qxd2 Ne4 14. Nxe4 Bxe4 $15) 12... Nd6 $5 {An ambitious idea to play for more,} ({simpler is} 12... Nxc3 13. Bxc3 Bxc3 14. bxc3 Ne4 15. Rd4 Qa5 $11) 13. Nd4 Nxc4 14. Qxc4 Bd3 15. Qb4 a5 {Black keeps the initiative ongoing.} 16. Qa3 Bc4 17. Rab1 ({or} 17. b3 Ba6 {with a likely transposition}) 17... Nd3 18. b3 Ba6 $44 {[%csl Ra3,Gd3]}) 11... Nce4 $1 {Contrary to the previous line, here is the right moment to jump on e4 with the other knight:} 12. Qe2 ({After} 12. Bb3 {Black can repeat by} Nc5 13. Bc2 {The only way to continue the fight for an opening advantage, but Black has sufficient resources at his disposal.} (13. Bc4 $11) 13... Bxc2 14. Qxc2 Nxd5 15. Rd1 e6 16. e4 ({or} 16. Nxd5 exd5 17. b4 Ne6 18. Qb3 d4 19. exd4 Nxd4 20. Nxd4 Bxd4 {with full equality}) 16... Nb4 {The equalizing point -} 17. Qb1 Qe7 $11) 12... Bg4 $1 {A precise move.} 13. Nxe4 ({In case of} 13. h3 Bxf3 14. gxf3 Nd6 15. Bb3 Qd7 {Black enjoys a very nice compensation for the pawn, for example} 16. Kg2 b5 17. a3 a5 $132) 13... Nxe4 14. h3 Bxf3 15. gxf3 Qc7 $1 {The key move for equality.} ({Black is slightly worse after} 15... Nd6 16. Bb3 Qd7 17. Kg2 $14) 16. fxe4 ({if} 16. Bb3 Nc5 $1 17. Bb4 {, then} Qd7 $1 {forces} 18. Bxc5 Rxc5 {with fine compensation due to the control over the dark squares -} 19. Kg2 a5 $44 {[%csl Gg7][%cal Gg7a1]}) 16... Qxc4 17. Qxc4 Rxc4 18. f3 f5 $1 {The endgame is approximately equal, for example} 19. Bh4 ({the pawn will be regained after} 19. exf5 Rxf5 20. e4 Rh5 {, even more, White is well-advised to take measures against the possible rook penetration on the penultimate rank, e. g.} 21. Kg2 Bxb2 22. Rb1 $140 $6 Bd4 23. Bf2 Rc2) 19... Bxb2 20. Rab1 Ba3 21. Rxb7 Re8 $1 {A necessary precaution, after which the peaceful end is quite near, for example} 22. Rxa7 Bc5 23. Rb7 fxe4 24. Bg5 exf3 25. Rxf3 Re4 $44 {/=}) (6. b4 {This move is asking for trouble.} c6 ({Another plan features} 6... Be6 $5 7. c5 Nbd7) 7. Bb2 ({In case of} 7. Be2 {Black can take over the initiative by means of} dxc4 $1 8. Bxc4 b5 $1 9. Be2 a5 10. bxa5 b4 11. Nb1 c5 $15) 7... Be6 {[%csl Rc4] Provoking some actions in the centre.} ({Other good options are} 7... a5) ({and} 7... Bg4) 8. c5 (8. cxd5 Nxd5 $11) 8... Nbd7 9. h3 {Prevents the pin from the g4-square, after which the central strike e7-e5 will be in the air.} b6 10. Bd3 a5 11. b5 ({Also equal is} 11. a3 axb4 12. axb4 Rxa1 13. Qxa1 Qc7 14. O-O Rb8 $11) 11... bxc5 12. bxc6 c4 13. cxd7 cxd3 14. O-O Nxd7 15. Qxd3 Rb8 16. Ba3 Nb6 17. Bc5 Qd7 $11 {Black is fine.}) (6. Bd3 $6 {looks inaccurate because of the thematic push} c5 $1 7. O-O (7. dxc5 dxc4 8. Bxc4 Qxd1+ 9. Nxd1 (9. Kxd1 Nbd7) 9... Ne4 $15 {[%csl Rc1][%cal Gg7a1]}) 7... cxd4 8. exd4 Nc6 9. h3 b6 $15 {[%cal Gc8b7] , once again with an easy game and better prospects for Black.}) (6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. Bc4 {A popular line during the last couple of years.} (7. Qb3 Nxc3 8. bxc3 c5 {transposes to the previous Chapter}) ({passive is} 7. Be2 c5 8. O-O $6 Nc6 $15) 7... Nb6 {Here I prefer this move.} (7... Nxc3 8. bxc3 c5 9. O-O Qc7 {is quite typical and fully playable as well}) 8. Bb3 c5 9. O-O (9. dxc5 $143 $6 N6d7) 9... cxd4 10. exd4 ({Harmless is} 10. Nxd4 Nc6 ({or} 10... Bd7 {[%cal Gb8c6] at first}) 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Qf3 (12. Qe2 a5 {[%cal Gc8a6]} 13. Rd1 Qc7) 12... a5 13. Rd1 Qc7 14. e4 a4 15. Bc2 Be6 $11 {I really like Black's chances, whose pieces are perfectly placed}) 10... Bg4 $1 {The best way to equalize.} ({A theoretical line goes on with} 10... Nc6 11. d5 Na5 12. h3) 11. d5 ({The alternatives are:} 11. Be3 Nc6 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Qxf3 Nxd4 {equalizes on the spot, while} (13... Na5 14. Rfe1 e6 $11 {is a plausible alternative}) 14. Qxb7 e5 $11) (11. h3 Bxf3 12. Qxf3 Nc6 13. d5 Nd4 $11) 11... N8d7 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Qxf3 Nc5 14. Re1 {[%cal Gc1g5] Placing the rook on the e-file is the most logical approach here,} ({in comparison to} 14. Rd1 Nxb3 15. axb3 Nc8 $11 {[%cal Gc8d6] A typical manoeuvre, Black is just fine}) 14... Nxb3 15. axb3 Re8 16. Bg5 (16. Be3 Nc8 $11) {Here Black can simplify by means of} 16... Bxc3 17. bxc3 Qxd5 18. Qxd5 Nxd5 19. c4 f6 $11 {with a likely draw.}) (6. Qb3 e6 {transposes to the previous Chapter.}) 6... c5 $1 {Once again this typical push is coming into the limelight.} 7. dxc5 ({The alternatives are harmless:} 7. O-O cxd4 8. exd4 Nc6 9. h3 dxc4 10. Bxc4 Na5 $11 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7] Black has no problems.}) ({If} 7. cxd5 cxd4 $1 8. Nxd4 (8. exd4 Nxd5 $11) 8... Nxd5 $11 {, then it is White, who should be careful here.}) 7... dxc4 $1 {Clearly the best option compared to} (7... Na6) ({and} 7... Qa5) 8. O-O ({In reply to} 8. Qa4 {Black has no problems after} Na6 $1 9. c6 ({otherwise White may quickly find himself in a worse position, e. g.} 9. O-O Nxc5 10. Qxc4 Qb6 $15 {[%cal Gc8e6]}) ({or} 9. Qxc4 Be6 10. Qb5 Nd5 $1 {A typical shot at the advantage -} 11. Nd4 Nxc3 12. bxc3 Bd7 13. Qxb7 Nxc5 14. Qb4 Ne4 $15 {[%cal Ga8b8]}) 9... Nc5 10. Qxc4 Qb6 11. O-O (11. b4 Nce4 $15) (11. cxb7 Bxb7 12. O-O Rac8 $15) 11... bxc6 12. b4 Nce4 13. Na4 Qb7 14. Bb2 a5 $15 {I believe that Black's game is easier.}) ({Inaccurate is} 8. Qxd8 $6 Rxd8 9. Bxc4 Nbd7 10. c6 bxc6 11. O-O Nb6 12. Be2 Bb7 $15 {[%cal Gc6c5]}) 8... Na6 $1 {This rare move is the best one in my opinion.} ({The main theoretical move is} 8... Qa5) 9. c6 ({Or} 9. Qd4 Qc7 10. Qxc4 Nxc5 $11 {[%cal Gc8e6]}) 9... Qc7 $5 {An interesting idea in order to fight for the advantage.} ({Another possibilities are} 9... Nb4) ({and} 9... Qb6) 10. Bxc4 ({The alternatives are} 10. cxb7 Bxb7 $132) ({and} 10. Qa4 Nc5 11. Qxc4 Qxc6 {[%cal Gc8e6] , which leads to mass exchanges of pieces after} 12. b4 (12. Nd4 Qb6 $11) 12... Nce4 13. Qxc6 bxc6 14. Bb2 a5 15. Nxe4 (15. bxa5 Rxa5 16. Nd4 Bd7 $11) 15... Nxe4 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. bxa5 Rxa5 $11 {The resulting endgame is completely equal.}) 10... Qxc6 11. b3 {An ambitious, but risky try.} ({Black has an easy equality after} 11. Qe2 Be6 $11) 11... Ne4 $1 {I believe that with the help of several precise moves Black must be able to fight for the advantage.} 12. Nxe4 ({Just bad is} 12. Nd5 $2 Qd6 $17) 12... Bxa1 13. Ba3 Bg7 {Preserving the bishop is the human handling of the position.} ({Instead,} 13... Qxe4 14. Qxa1 $13 {is far from clear.}) 14. Neg5 Qf6 $1 {Still, a very accurate play is required.} 15. Qd3 b5 $1 {Clearly the best move, Black is already taking over the initiative.} 16. Bxb5 Rb8 17. Bc4 Nb4 18. Qd2 Nc6 $15 {White still has some compensation, but I would definitely prefer Black here.} *

