{[%evp 0,54,31,20,29,10,42,42,46,46,38,12,59,24,14,21,59,44,-15,30,0,-12,5,-1,44,17,8,10,-4,12,0,0,17,-40,17,-13,18,10,60,26,16,16,10,0,9,0,-6,-13,-1,0,5,31,11,-12,6,18,-2]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. h4 $5 {This line is quite popular nowadays. I believe Black has different ways to obtain good chances, but the handling of such unbalanced positions usually requires a lot of knowledge.} dxc4 {The most aggressive approach.} ({Much more solid is} 5... c6 6. cxd5 cxd5 7. Bf4) 6. e4 ({Harmless is} 6. Qa4+ Nc6 7. Qxc4 O-O 8. e4 e5 9. dxe5 Ng4 10. Nd5 Be6 $132 {[%cal Gg4e5]}) 6... O-O ({Another trendy line is} 6... c5 7. d5 b5 8. h5 O-O $13) 7. Bxc4 ({The alternatives are simply worse for White:} 7. h5 $6 Nxh5 8. Bxc4 (8. e5 $6 c5 $17) 8... Bg4 9. Be3 Nd7 $5 {Probably the best, although there is nothing wrong with} (9... c5) ({or} 9... Nc6) 10. Qb3 Bxf3 11. gxf3 Nb6 12. O-O-O Nxc4 13. Qxc4 Qd7 $15 {I don't think that White has full compensation for the sacrificed pawn.}) (7. e5 $6 Ng4 $1 8. h5 c5 9. hxg6 hxg6 10. d5 ({in case of} 10. Bxc4 $6 cxd4 11. Ne4 Nc6 $17 {Black is clearly better}) 10... Nd7 {White's centre is about to collapse -} 11. e6 fxe6 12. Bxc4 Nde5 13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14. Be2 b5 $1 15. f4 Nc4 $17) 7... c5 8. d5 ({The rest moves are just failing to impress:} 8. h5 cxd4 $5 {In connection with the next sequence - the most direct and classical reaction to the early impudent aggression.} ({The capture of the brave pawn} 8... Nxh5 9. d5 Bg4 10. Rh4 Qd7 $13 {is also possible}) 9. hxg6 hxg6 10. Qxd4 Qxd4 11. Nxd4 Nxe4 {I believe that it is White, who should fight for equality.} 12. Nxe4 Bxd4 13. Bh6 Bg7 14. Ng5 Nc6 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. Rh7+ Kf6 17. f4 ({If} 17. Ne4+ {, then} Ke5 {looks sufficient}) 17... Bf5 18. Nxf7 Na5 $1 {A very important intermediate move.} 19. Ne5 Nxc4 20. Nxc4 Be4 $15 {Black has slightly better chances in the endgame.}) ({Apparently premature is} 8. e5 $6 Ng4 $15) 8... b5 $1 {The key move for Black's plan.} 9. Bxb5 ({The other way to capture the pawn does not bring any dividends, as witnessed by} 9. Nxb5 Nxe4 10. h5 (10. O-O $6 a6 11. Nc3 Nxc3 12. bxc3 Bg4 $15 {Hammer - Bok, Aix les Bains, 2011}) 10... Nd7 11. Qe2 Ndf6 12. Ne5 Bb7 $132 {with a very complex game. It should be noted that all of Black's pieces are already very well coordinated.}) 9... Nxe4 $1 10. Nxe4 Qa5+ 11. Nc3 Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 Qxb5 13. h5 ({The alternatives are less dangerous:} 13. Ne5 f6 $132) (13. Bh6 Rd8 14. Ne5 Bf5 $1 15. Qf3 ({Or} 15. h5 f6) 15... Nd7 16. Nc6 Re8 17. h5 Qc4 18. Rd1 f6 $15 {[%csl Re1] The White's king is much more exposed.}) (13. Qb3 Ba6 $1 14. Qxb5 Bxb5 15. h5 Nd7 16. hxg6 hxg6 $11 {with equal endgame.}) 13... Qc4 $1 {Yet another forced move.} 14. hxg6 {The insertion of this exchange is very logical. The alternatives are:} (14. Bg5 $6 {This sally is wasting valuable time -} Ba6 $15 {and the e7-pawn is poisoned}) (14. Qd2 {[%cal Gd2h6] A new, but quite logical and frightening idea.} Ba6 $1 {The most natural response.} (14... Bg4 $5 {is a probable alternative}) {From the other side, the insertion of} 15. hxg6 ({The attempt for} 15. Ne5 Qe4+ 16. Qe3 Qxg2 17. Rh4 {is supposedly leading to a draw by perpetual, for example} f6 18. Nxg6 hxg6 19. Qe6+ Rf7 ({or} 19... Kg7 20. Qxe7+ Kg8 $11) 20. hxg6 Qf1+ 21. Kd2 Qd3+ $11) 15... fxg6 16. Qe3 Qxd5 {before} 17. Rxh7 $5 {looks tempting as well.} ({If the opponents prefer to call it a day, then there is} 17. Qxe7 Rf7 18. Qe8+ Rf8 $11) 17... Kxh7 18. Qh6+ Kg8 19. Qxg6+ Kh8 20. c4 $5 {White can try this, but the final result will be the same.} (20. Qh6+ $11) 20... Qxc4 21. Bb2+ Rf6 22. Bxf6+ exf6 23. Qxf6+ Kg8 24. Qd8+ $11) (14. Rh4 Qxc3+ 15. Bd2 Qd3 {transposes to the main line.}) 14... fxg6 15. Rh4 {Perhaps the most dangerous of the existing options:} (15. Qd2 Ba6 {transposes to 14.î Bd2.}) (15. Bh6 Rd8 (15... Rf5 $5) 16. Qb3 Qxb3 17. axb3 Rxd5 18. c4 Rf5 $11 {White has some compensation, but nothing more.}) 15... Qxc3+ ({But not} 15... Bg4 $2 {because of} 16. Nd2 $1 Bxd1 17. Nxc4 Ba4 18. Bg5 $18 {White wins.}) 16. Bd2 Qd3 $1 {The critical position for the whole line. White has two main tries here, namely 17.î Ph6 and 17.î Pg5.} 17. Bh6 (17. Bg5 Qxd1+ 18. Rxd1 Rf5 $1 {An important move.} (18... Nd7 $6 {is premature, for} 19. Re4 $14 {poses new problems, the text is opposing exactly such rook lift}) 19. Re4 ({Here are the possible alternatives in brief -} 19. d6 exd6 20. Rxd6 Nd7 $11) ({or} 19. Bxe7 Nd7 20. d6 Bb7 $11 {when Nd7 perfectly blockades the d-pawn}) 19... Bb7 $1 {(the key to counterplay)} 20. Rxe7 ({The rook can invade on the penultimate rank but at the cost of the precious central pawn.} 20. Re5 {is a clever try to preserve it on the board, but Black can insist with} Nd7 21. Rxe7 Rd8 $1 {A necessary move - the last piece is joining the game and the threat against the d5-pawn is resumed. Now the game can continue with} 22. Bh6 Bxd5 23. Rg7+ Kh8 24. Ng5 Re8+ 25. Kf1 Rxg5 26. Bxg5 Bc4+ 27. Kg1 Kxg7 28. Rxd7+ Bf7 $11 {with an obvious draw.}) 20... Bxd5 21. g4 {The only serious try for more.} (21. Re8+ Kf7 22. Re7+ $11) 21... Rxf3 22. Bh6 ({The alternative} 22. Rxd5 {looks frightening, but Black is just in time to mobilize his army -} Nc6 23. Rc7 Re8+ 24. Kf1 Re5 $11) (22. Re8+ Kf7 23. Re7+ Kg8 $11) 22... Nc6 23. Rg7+ Kh8 24. Rxd5 Rh3 $1 {A very important nuance.} 25. g5 Nd4 26. Rdd7 ({Or} 26. Rxa7 Re8+ 27. Kf1 Ne6 28. Re5 Kg8 29. a4 c4 $11 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Gc4c3]}) 26... Nf5 $1 {Remarkably enough, the knight is saving the king in alone!} 27. Rxh7+ Kg8 28. Rxa7 Ra3 ({or} 28... Rxa7 29. Rxa7 c4 $11) 29. Rxa8+ Rxa8 30. Rc7 Nxh6 31. gxh6 Rxa2 $11) ({In case of} 17. Be3 {Black can also play} Qc3+ $5 ({good enough is} 17... Qxd1+ 18. Rxd1 Nd7 19. Re4 Re8 $11) 18. Kf1 (18. Bd2 Qd3 $11) 18... Ba6+ 19. Kg1 Be2 $1 {The point!} 20. Qxe2 Qxa1+ 21. Kh2 Nd7 {Now White's best is to force a draw with the help of the spectacular} 22. Bd4 $1 cxd4 23. Qe6+ Rf7 24. Rxh7 (24. Ng5 $2 Raf8 25. Rxh7 d3 $17 {[%cal Ga1e5]}) 24... Kxh7 25. Ng5+ Kh6 26. Nxf7+ Kg7 27. Qxe7 d3 28. Ng5+ Kh6 29. Nf7+ $11 {with perpetual check.}) 17... Qxd1+ 18. Rxd1 Rf5 $1 {The best move in my opinion.} ({Otherwise,} 18... Re8 {is the more popular continuation in the practice.}) 19. d6 ({The other critical move is} 19. Re4 {, when Black is initiating counterplay in a highly instructive way -} Nd7 $1 20. Rxe7 Rh5 $1 {[%cal Gh5h1] A key defensive resource, similar to 24...Rh3! in a note from above.} 21. Be3 ({Black seems in order after the other retreats of the bishop, as shown by} 21. Bc1 Nb6 22. Ne5 Rh1+ 23. Kd2 Rxd1+ 24. Kxd1 Nxd5 25. Re8+ Kg7 26. Bb2 Bb7 $11) ({and} 21. Bg7 Nb6 22. d6 Rh1+ 23. Kd2 Nc4+ 24. Ke2 Rxd1 25. Kxd1 Nxd6 26. Bf6 Bg4 27. Rg7+ Kf8 28. Rxh7 Nf7 {(yet another proper example that the knight is the best defender of the own king!)} 29. Rh4 Be6 $11 {[%csl Gf7] Black is finally in safety}) 21... Nf6 ({moving to the opposite direction by} 21... Nb6 22. d6 Bg4 {is a reasonable choice either}) 22. d6 Bg4 $11 {and Black equalized in Fedoseev - Chigaev, Moscow, 2020.}) 19... e5 $1 {It is important to gain some activity and space.} ({The passive} 19... e6 $6 20. Re4 $14 {is evidently a concession.}) 20. Be3 ({The other tries are:} 20. Ng5 Nd7 21. Rb1 ({If} 21. g4 {then good is} Rf4 $1 22. Nxh7 Rd4 $1 23. Be3 Rxd1+ 24. Kxd1 Rb8 25. Ng5 Rb6 $11 {and Black is out of danger}) 21... Rb8 $1 {It is a good idea to exchange a pair of rooks.} 22. Rxb8 Nxb8 23. Ne4 Nd7 24. Be3 Rh5 25. Rxh5 gxh5 26. Nxc5 Nxc5 27. Bxc5 a6 $11 {with an absolute draw.}) (20. Rb1 Rf6 $1 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gf6d6] Here this is the best defense.} 21. Be3 ({or} 21. Nxe5 Rxd6) 21... Rxd6 22. Bxc5 Rd5 $11) 20... Nd7 21. Ng5 h5 22. Rc4 Ba6 23. Rc3 Bb7 24. Kf1 ({Or} 24. f3 Re8 {with mutual chances.}) 24... e4 $5 ({Here too,} 24... Re8 {is a plausible alternative.}) 25. Ne6 Kf7 26. Nxc5 (26. Nc7 {does not bring much after} Rb8 $11) 26... Nxc5 27. Bxc5 ({Similar is} 27. Rxc5 Rxc5 28. Bxc5 Ke6 $11 {, when, as usual, the opposite-coloured bishops are the presage of a draw.}) 27... Ke6 $11 {The endgame is equal.} *

