{[%evp 0,54,28,20,28,10,40,33,46,33,27,25,69,33,33,46,74,60,45,37,36,45,83,42,45,40,40,37,29,26,29,26,27,27,20,14,10,14,23,8,20,25,29,12,31,31,25,29,45,28,28,25,11,26,19,28,36]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bf4 {This line is known to be very solid for White and it is usually preferred by players who like to play for an opening advantage without risk.} Bg7 5. e3 {The best move order. 5.î ..f3 will be seen in the next lesson.} ({Another possibility is} 5. Rc1 {, when Black can immediately make use of the powerful fianchettoed bishop by means of the concrete} Nh5 $5 (5... dxc4) ({and} 5... O-O {are the main alternatives}) 6. Bg5 ({the bizarre} 6. Be3 $6 {has a drawback -} dxc4 $1 {, urging the queen to enter the game at a very early stage -} 7. Qa4+ Nc6 8. Nf3 Be6 $1 9. Ng5 $140 Bd7 10. Qxc4 O-O $15 {[%cal Ge7e5] Black is already better in the view of the coming e7-e5}) (6. Bd2 c5 ({good enough is} 6... dxc4 7. e3 c5 $11) 7. e3 cxd4 8. exd4 dxc4 9. Nf3 O-O 10. Bxc4 Bg4 11. d5 Nd7 $11 {[%cal Gd7e5] and Black is absolutely fine}) 6... h6 {I like this idea to question White's bishop.} ({fully possible is} 6... dxc4) 7. Bd2 (7. Bh4 $143 $6 c5 $1 {and Black is seizing the initiative, e. g.} 8. Nxd5 Nc6 9. e3 cxd4 $15) 7... c5 8. e3 ({if} 8. cxd5 cxd4 9. Nb5 Na6 10. Nxd4 Qxd5 $11 {, then only White should be worried here.}) 8... cxd4 ({Black is fine after} 8... dxc4 9. dxc5 Nd7 $11 {as well}) 9. exd4 dxc4 10. d5 a6 11. Bxc4 Nd7 $132 {[%cal Gb7b5] Black has decent chances in the long run, the isolated d-pawn is not in safety at all.}) 5... c5 {This is the move that I would like to suggest.} ({Indeed,} 5... O-O {is a major alternative.}) 6. dxc5 Qa5 7. Rc1 {The main move.} (7. Qa4+ {is another popular line. The theory has already proved that Black is doing very well here.} Qxa4 8. Nxa4 Bd7 {The most common and direct approach.} ({Also known are} 8... Be6) ({and} 8... O-O) 9. Nc3 Ne4 $1 {The point!} 10. Nge2 {is a rare and not that challenging move.} (10. Nxd5 Na6 {[%csl Rc7] Black must start with this move.} 11. f3 Nexc5 12. O-O-O {The most logical continuation.} (12. Rb1 e6 (12... Rc8 {is a sound alternative}) 13. Nc7+ (13. Nc3 Bxc3+ $1 {A very typical exchange in this line. The queens are gone, so Black can part with the bishop in order to wreck White's pawn structure.} 14. bxc3 f6 $15 {[%cal Ge6e5,Gd7e6] The endgame is very attractive, the next is to push the e-pawn and place the bishop on the liberated e6-square.}) 13... Nxc7 14. Bxc7 Na4 $132 {[%cal Ga4b2,Ga4c3]}) (12. Bg5 {is well countered by} Bxb2 13. Rb1 f6 {with comfortable position after} 14. Rxb2 fxg5 $11 {in Dreev - Gopal, Zuerich, 2009}) 12... e6 13. Nc7+ (13. Nc3 Bxc3 $1 {Here we are again!} 14. bxc3 f6 {[%cal Ge6e5]} 15. e4 e5 16. Be3 Rc8 $15 {[%csl Rc3,Rc4] I definitely prefer Black, Akobian - So, Saint Louis, 2018.}) 13... Nxc7 14. Bxc7 Rc8 ({the immediate} 14... b5 $5 {is also worth considering}) 15. Bg3 (15. Bd6 b5 $1 16. b3 Nb7 {[%cal Gb7d6]} ({very tempting is} 16... bxc4 $5 17. Bxc4 Na4 {[%cal Ga4c3,Gd7b5]}) 17. Kb1 ({White should probably better keep the bishop -} 17. Bb4 bxc4 18. Bxc4 {, when Black will take the pawn back -} Bb5 $11) 17... Nxd6 18. Rxd6 Ke7 19. Rd1 a6 $5 {A winning attempt.} (19... bxc4 20. Bxc4 Rxc4 21. bxc4 Rb8+ 22. Kc1 Ba4 23. Rd2 Rb4 {with perpetual check after} 24. Ne2 Rxc4+ 25. Kb1 Rb4+ $11) 20. cxb5 axb5 21. Ne2 Rhd8 $44 {[%csl Rb1,Gd7,Gg7] I would definitely prefer Black, the bishops are extremely strong.}) 15... b5 ({the knight's cruise can continue with} 15... Na4 16. b3 Nc3 17. Rd2 Nd5 {[%csl Re3][%cal Gd5e3]} 18. e4 Ne3 19. Ne2 b5 20. c5 Rxc5+ 21. Kb1 Bh6 $11 {and Black is at least not worse}) 16. b3 bxc4 17. Bxc4 Na4 {[%cal Ga4c3,Ga4b2]} 18. Kd2 ({If} 18. Ne2 $2 {then} Nb2 $17) 18... Nc3 19. Re1 Bb5 $5 (19... Nxa2 20. Ne2 $11) 20. Bxb5+ Nxb5 {and returning the pawn by} 21. Ne2 Ke7 {[%cal Gh8d8]} 22. Rc1 Rhd8+ 23. Nd4 {should enable White to hold, for instance} Nxd4 24. exd4 Bh6+ 25. f4 Rxd4+ {, when} 26. Ke2 $1 $11 {seems to be the best way to anticipate the possible doubling of the rooks along the d-file.}) 10... Nxc5 11. Nxd5 (11. cxd5 $143 $6 Nd3+ 12. Kd2 Nxf2 13. Rg1 Na6 $15) 11... Nba6 {with ample compensation for the pawn, for example} 12. Nec3 ({In case of} 12. O-O-O $6 {good is} Ne4 $1 {[%csl Rf2]} 13. Bg3 Rc8 $36) 12... e6 13. Nc7+ Nxc7 14. Bxc7 Bxc3+ $1 15. bxc3 f6 $44 {[%csl Rc3,Rc4][%cal Ga8c8,Ge6e5] I believe only Black can be better in this endgame.}) (7. cxd5 $6 {This line was supposed to end in a forced draw, but the strongest engines have changed the evaluation to a very dangerous for White.} Nxd5 $1 {A typical tactical shot along the big diagonal.} 8. Qxd5 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Qxc3+ 10. Ke2 Qxa1 11. Be5 Qb1 $1 {This is the move that gives Black excellent chances, it is important to protect the b7-pawn.} ({Black does not have more than a draw by perpetual after} 11... Qc1 12. Bxh8 Be6 13. Qxb7 Qc2+ $11) 12. Bxh8 Be6 13. Qd3 Qxa2+ 14. Kf3 ({clearly worse is} 14. Ke1 $2 f6 15. Bg7 Na6 $19 {[%csl Re1][%cal Ga8d8]}) 14... f6 15. Bg7 Nd7 {[%cal Gd7e5]} 16. Kg3 Rc8 $40 {[%csl Rg3][%cal Gd7c5,Gc8c5,Gd7e5] I believe that White's position is extremely dangerous.}) ({In case of} 7. Qb3 {Black equalizes easily after} dxc4 8. Bxc4 ({risky is} 8. Qxc4 O-O $132 {[%cal Gc8e6]}) 8... O-O 9. Qb5 {Trading the queens is necessary, otherwise Black is able to regain the pawn and grab the initiative by harassing ?b3, for example} (9. Nge2 Nbd7 {[%cal Gd7c5]}) ({or} 9. Nf3 Ne4 10. O-O Nxc5 $11) 9... Qxb5 10. Bxb5 (10. Nxb5 $144 Na6) 10... Bd7 11. Be2 Bc6 12. Nf3 Nbd7 $11 {N:c5 with a roughly equal endgame.}) (7. Nf3 {is aimed mostly at neutralizing the mighty ?g7. A direct shot at equality is} Ne4 8. Be5 Nxc3 9. Qd2 Bxe5 10. Nxe5 f6 11. Nf3 dxc4 12. Bxc4 Qb4 ({Black can also start with} 12... Nd7 13. c6 Nc5 $11) 13. Qxc3 Qxc3+ 14. bxc3 Nd7 $11 {[%cal Gd7c5] and White's extra pawn is once again of temporary character.}) 7... dxc4 8. Bxc4 O-O ({Black should be aware of the tactical omission} 8... Qxc5 $2 {, which is leading to a disaster after} 9. Nb5 $1 {[%cal Gb5c7]} Qb4+ 10. Kf1 Na6 11. a3 Qxb2 12. Rb1 $18 {and White won material in Leitao - Van Wely, Antwerp, 1998.}) 9. Nf3 {The most natural move.} ({The other jump} 9. Nge2 {has been popular in the past.} Qxc5 10. Qb3 ({here} 10. Nb5 $2 {does not work in the view of} Qb4+ $1 11. Kf1 Ne4 $17 {[%cal Ge4d2]}) 10... Qa5 $1 {This well-timed retreat is the easiest way to equalize.} ({Instead, the natural} 10... Nc6 $6 {allows} 11. Nb5 $1 {, forcing Black's queen to search a safe square on the kingside, but there is no relief for it after} Qh5 12. Ng3 Qh4 13. Nc7 {I don't deliberately suggest this suspicious line, because it is requiring clinical precision from Black, who needs to know a lot to survive}) 11. O-O Nbd7 $1 {[%cal Gd7b6,Gd7e5,Gd7c5] One more subtle move, preparing actions in the centre, after which Black is doing fine. The knight is much more flexible here in comparison to its usual c6-location.} 12. h3 (12. a3 Ne5 $1 ({senseless is} 12... Nb6 $6 {because of} 13. Bc7 $1) 13. Bxe5 ({Black is doing fine after both} 13. Bb5 Be6) ({and} 13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. Bxd5 Bd7 $11) 13... Qxe5 $11 {Black does not have any problems.}) (12. Rfd1 Nc5 $1 {Wisely switching to the queenside.} (12... Ne5 $2 {is now wrong in the view of the powerful} 13. Nd5 $1 $18 {and White wins}) ({similarly,} 12... Nb6 $6 13. Bc7 $14 {does not solve the opening tasks}) 13. Qb5 Qxb5 14. Nxb5 ({or} 14. Bxb5 a6 15. Bc4 Be6 16. Bxe6 Nxe6 17. Be5 Rfd8 $11) 14... Be6 $1 15. Bxe6 Nxe6 16. Be5 {This position occurred in the game M. Matlakov - C. Li, Novi Sad, 2016, when the simplest road to equality is} Rfd8 $11) 12... Nc5 $1 {Aimed at trading the queens.} (12... Ne5 $6 {is imprecise here as well, albeit not so bad as in the previous note. The same jump} 13. Nd5 $1 {is also critical -} Nxd5 14. Bxd5 Bd7 15. Rfd1 $16) 13. Qb5 Qxb5 14. Nxb5 Bd7 15. Nec3 (15. Rfd1 Na4 {[%cal Ga4b2,Ga4b6]} ({safe enough is} 15... Rfd8) 16. Be5 Nb6 17. Bd3 {So far Feletar - Schmelz, ICCF email, 2019. Black has many ways to equalize here and} Nfd5 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 $11 {is just one of them}) 15... Rfd8 16. Rfd1 Ne8 {Perhaps the safest move, Black has for sure other reasonable alternatives as well.} 17. Bd5 (17. Bg5 Bf6 $11) (17. Nc7 Rac8 18. Nxe8 Bxe8 $11) 17... Be6 18. b3 a6 19. Nc7 Nxc7 20. Bxc7 Rd7 $11 {with a balanced game, Blanco Gramajo - Martin Sanchez, ICCF email, 2020.}) 9... Qxc5 {The main move.} ({Black has lately tried} 9... Nbd7 $5 {[%cal Gd7c5] either.}) 10. Bb3 ({All the other moves are pretty harmless:} 10. Qb3 Nc6 {[%cal Gc6a5]} 11. O-O Na5 12. Qb5 Qxc4 13. Qxa5 b6 14. Qa3 Re8 {Black's position is very safe -} 15. Rfd1 Qa6 $1 16. Qb4 ({Or} 16. Qb3 Be6 17. Qb5 Bc4 $11) 16... Bb7 17. Ne5 Rac8 18. h3 Rc5 $11 {with comfortable play in the game Radjabov - So, chess24.com INT, 2020.}) (10. Nb5 $6 {is dubious in the view of} Be6 $1) 10... Bg4 $1 {The newest approach and the easiest way for Black to equalize.} ({The old main theory goes on with} 10... Nc6 11. O-O Qa5) 11. O-O ({Another important option is} 11. h3 Qh5 {and now:} 12. Rg1 {The point of this move is to keep the king in the centre for the upcoming endgame.} (12. Bh2 Bxf3 13. Qxf3 Qxf3 14. gxf3 Nc6 15. Ke2 Rfc8 {This endgame looks quite balanced.} 16. Rhd1 e6 17. a3 ({or} 17. Nb5 Ne8 {[%csl Rb2,Rc7,Rd6][%cal Gg7b2]}) 17... Na5 18. Ba2 Ne8 19. Rd3 b5 20. Rcd1 a6 $11 {Weber - Tiemann, ICCF email, 2020}) 12... Bxf3 13. Qxf3 Qxf3 14. gxf3 Nc6 (14... Rc8 {is quite normal and Black can start with it}) 15. Ke2 Rfc8 16. Nd5 ({if} 16. Rgd1 {, then possible is} Na5) 16... Rd8 $5 {This move is by far not the only reliable option, but it is definitely the most concrete one - Black is provoking exchanges.} 17. Rc5 ({Or} 17. Nxf6+ Bxf6 $11 {[%csl Rb2]}) 17... Rac8 18. Rd1 e6 19. Nxf6+ Bxf6 20. Rxd8+ Rxd8 $11 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Gf6b2]}) 11... Qh5 12. h3 (12. Nd5 {looks tempting, but in fact, Black has no problems after:} Nc6 13. Rxc6 ({harmless is} 13. h3 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 Qxf3 15. gxf3 Rfd8 16. Rfd1 e6 17. Nxf6+ Bxf6 $11 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Gf6b2]}) 13... Nxd5 $1 {An obligatory intermediate capture.} ({in case of} 13... bxc6 $6 14. Nxe7+ Kh8 15. Nxc6 Ne4 16. Qd5 $1 Qxd5 17. Bxd5 Nf6 18. Bb3 $14 {and White preserves pressure for the sacrificed exchange}) 14. Rc5 Bxf3 15. gxf3 e6 16. Bxd5 ({but not} 16. e4 $2 b6) 16... Rad8 $1 {[%cal Gd8d5] The ultimate equalizer - Black is regaining the piece with interest.} 17. Kg2 ({similar is} 17. Qb3 b6 18. Rb5 Rxd5 19. Rxd5 Qxd5 20. Qxd5 exd5 21. b3 d4 $11 {Beliavsky - Volokitin, Bled, 2016.}) 17... b6 18. Rb5 Rxd5 19. Rxd5 Qxd5 20. Qxd5 exd5 21. b3 d4 $11) 12... Bxf3 13. Qxf3 Qxf3 14. gxf3 Nc6 15. Rfd1 Rfd8 {White has the pair of bishops, but there are no weaknesses in the opponent's camp, so the endgame must be assessed as equal.} 16. Ba4 ({Or} 16. Kf1 Rxd1+ ({worth of attention is} 16... Na5 $5) 17. Rxd1 Rd8 18. Rxd8+ Nxd8 19. Ke2 {This position occurred in the game Fedoseev - Chigaev, Chess.com INT, 2020. Here Black could play} Nd7 20. Kd2 Ne5 21. Bd1 f5 22. Be2 Kf7 $11) 16... Rxd1+ 17. Rxd1 Rd8 18. Rxd8+ ({Black is pretty safe in case of} 18. Bxc6 Rxd1+ 19. Nxd1 bxc6 $11 {[%cal Gf6d5]}) 18... Nxd8 19. Kf1 {The endgame looks slightly better for White because of the pair of bishops, but it is hard to achieve anything substantial.} Kf8 20. Ke2 Ne8 21. Bb8 Bxc3 $5 {Even this is possible.} 22. bxc3 a6 {It seems that the knights are fighting on equal terms against the bishops.} 23. Bf4 ({If} 23. Kd3 {then} Ne6 $1 {[%cal Ge6c5] and White's king is going nowhere.}) 23... f6 24. Bh6+ Kf7 25. Bb3+ e6 26. e4 Nd6 27. Be3 Nc6 $11 {Black's pawn structure is very solid, so the draw is the most likely outcome, Noire - Fichtner, ICCF email, 2009.} *

