{[%evp 0,56,25,20,21,10,33,33,50,47,54,33,16,19,50,28,7,9,9,9,9,11,-9,19,-1,13,13,13,42,42,35,15,24,2,19,-3,43,40,52,-2,-25,-31,-47,-31,-34,-22,-25,-28,-25,-27,-27,-32,-23,-15,-22,-13,-17,-43,-30]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bf4 O-O 6. Rc1 {This move order was quite popular for a long. Nowadays, the theory shows that Black is equalizing quite easily.} (6. e3 $6 {This move order is not so good for White. I believe that Black can already obtain a small plus with the help of the typical} c5 $1 7. dxc5 Ne4 $1 {The point! White should tread with great care.} 8. Rc1 {The only decent move in comparison to the alternatives} (8. Nxd5 Na6 $15 {[%cal Gg7b2,Ga6c5,Gd8a5] with plenty of initiative for the sacrificed pawns}) ({and} 8. Be5 Bxe5 9. Nxe5 Nxc3 10. bxc3 Be6 11. cxd5 Bxd5 $15 {[%csl Rc3,Rc5] , when Black simply has a better pawn structure}) 8... Nd7 $1 {An important move order.} 9. cxd5 (9. Nxd5 $6 {is like playing with fire -} e6 10. Bc7 Qe8 11. Nc3 Bxc3+ $1 {The most accurate.} 12. Rxc3 ({Or} 12. bxc3 Ndxc5 $15) 12... Nxc3 13. bxc3 Nxc5 14. Bd6 b6 15. Bxf8 Qxf8 $15 {[%csl Rc3,Rc4][%cal Gc8a6] with very pleasant play on the queenside}) 9... Qa5 $1 {A critical position has arisen. Here White has a large choice:} 10. Nd4 {The most logical move for protecting his Nc3 by blocking the scope of the g7-bishop.} (10. Qc2 Nxc3 11. bxc3 Nxc5 12. Nd4 (12. e4 $143 Bd7 $15 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gd7a4]}) (12. Nd2 Bd7 $15 {cannot inspire White either}) 12... e5 $1 {The most convincing way to rich counterplay.} (12... Nd7 $5 {[%cal Ga5d5,Gd7b6]}) 13. dxe6 Bxe6 14. Nxe6 Nxe6 {[%csl Ra2,Rc3][%cal Ge6f4] White has too many weaknesses.} 15. Be2 Rac8 {[%csl Rc3]} 16. O-O Rxc3 17. Qb1 Nxf4 18. exf4 Re8 $11 {The game is about equal, but White is the one who is suffering a bit}) (10. Nd2 {is passive -} Nxc3 11. bxc3 Nxc5 $15 {[%csl Ra2,Rc3][%cal Gc8d7,Ga8c8]}) (10. Be2 Nxc3 11. bxc3 Bxc3+ 12. Kf1 Nxc5 {Black's position is definitely very promising -} 13. Ne5 (13. Qc2 $143 $6 Na4 $17) ({no better is} 13. h4 Bd7 $15 {[%cal Gd7a4]}) 13... Bxe5 $1 {The best.} 14. Bxe5 b6 $15 {[%csl Rf1][%cal Ga5a2,Gc8a6] with excellent prospects on the queenside and against the d-pawn in particular}) (10. Bc4 {The bishop will be very vulnerable on this square after} Nxc3 11. bxc3 Bxc3+ 12. Kf1 Nxc5 $15 {[%csl Rc4]}) 10... Nxc3 11. bxc3 Qxa2 $1 {[%csl Rc5,Rd5][%cal Ga2d5,Gd7c5] Here it is important to take this pawn, thus keeping an eye on White's central pawns.} 12. c6 (12. Qb3 $143 $6 Qxb3 13. Nxb3 a5 {[%cal Ga5a4] The march of this pawn sends a worrying signal to the opponent, after} 14. c6 bxc6 15. dxc6 Nb6 $17 {Black is clearly on top}) (12. Nb3 a5 13. e4 Qb2 $15 {[%cal Ga5a4] is also looking very unpleasant for White}) 12... Nc5 13. Be2 Qxd5 14. Bf3 ({or} 14. O-O e5 $15) 14... Qd8 {I think that Black should prefer the text and play on.} ({Instead, in several games} 14... Qc4 {led to draws by repetition after} 15. Be2 $11) 15. O-O e5 16. Bg3 Qe7 $15 {[%csl Ga7][%cal Ga7a1] My belief is that White will suffer a lot in an actual game.}) 6... dxc4 7. e3 ({The more aggressive approach is} 7. e4 {, to which} c5 {is trendy nowadays.} ({The old main line} 7... Bg4 $5 8. Bxc4 Nh5 {is also good}) 8. dxc5 {White has practically nothing better, as shown by} (8. d5 $6 b5 $1 9. Nxb5 Qa5+ 10. Nc3 Nxe4 $15) ({or} 8. e5 $2 Nh5 $17 {[%csl Rd4,Re5][%cal Gb8c6]}) 8... Qa5 9. Nd2 {The only decent move.} ({Of course not} 9. Bxc4 $2 Nxe4 $17) ({Also dubious is} 9. e5 $6 Nh5 10. Bd2 ({White will not equalize after} 10. Be3 Rd8 11. Nd2 ({or} 11. Qa4 Qxa4 12. Nxa4 Nc6 13. Bxc4 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. O-O Bd7 {[%cal Gd7c6]} 16. Nc3 Bc6 $15 {and all Black's minor pieces are optimally placed}) 11... Bxe5 12. Bxc4 Nc6 $36) 10... Qxc5 11. Be3 (11. h3 $143 Bxe5 12. Be3 Qd6 $15) 11... Qa5 12. Qd5 $5 ({if} 12. Bxc4 {, then the central pawn is in trouble after} Nc6) 12... Qxd5 {The simplest.} (12... Nc6 $5 {is more aggressive -} 13. Qxa5 Nxa5 14. h3 f6 $1 {The point is that after 15.g4 the capture of the e5-pawn is attacking Nf3, so} 15. Nd5 fxe5 16. Nc7 Rb8 17. Bxa7 e4 $132 {[%cal Gg7b2] with wild complications}) 13. Nxd5 Nc6 14. Bxc4 Bg4 15. Bb5 Nxe5 16. Nxe7+ Kh8 $11 {with excellent play for Black in S. Mamedyarov - Y. Lou, China, 2015.}) 9... Be6 10. Bxc4 (10. Nxc4 $143 $6 Bxc4 11. Bxc4 Nxe4 $15) 10... Bxc4 11. Nxc4 Qxc5 12. b3 (12. Qe2 Nc6 $11) 12... Nc6 13. Be3 Qh5 {Forced, but good enough.} 14. Qxh5 Nxh5 15. g4 ({In case of} 15. Ke2 {Black can try} f5 $5 (15... Rfd8) 16. exf5 gxf5 17. f4 Rad8 18. Rhd1 Kf7 $11 {with equal chances}) 15... Bxc3+ $5 $146 {An interesting improvement.} ({There is nothing wrong with} 15... Nf6 16. f3 Rfd8 17. Ke2 Ne8 {[%cal Ge8c7,Gc7e6] , when Black is a bit passive, but very solid -} 18. Rhd1 Nc7 19. f4 Rxd1 20. Nxd1 {So far Dreev - Popilski, Caleta, 2014, and now} Ne6 $11) 16. Rxc3 Ng7 {[%cal Gf7f5]} 17. f4 ({Or} 17. Ke2 Rad8) 17... f5 $1 {The point of Black's plan.} (17... Rad8 $5) 18. gxf5 (18. exf5 gxf5 19. Rg1 fxg4 20. Rxg4 Rf5 $11 {is about equal as well}) 18... gxf5 19. Rg1 fxe4 20. Ne5 ({Or} 20. Nd2 Rf6 {[%cal Gf6g6] The simplest reply -} 21. Nxe4 Rg6 $11) 20... Nxe5 21. fxe5 Rf3 {The position remains balanced in spite of its concrete character, for example} 22. e6 Rf6 23. Rc7 (23. Bd4 $143 $6 Rg6) 23... Rxe6 24. Bd4 {Leads to mass exchanges.} ({In case of} 24. Rxb7 Kf7 25. Bxa7 Nf5 $11 {[%csl Ge4,Ge6,Gf5] Black has definitely a lot of counterplay}) 24... Rg6 25. Rxe7 Nf5 26. Rxg6+ hxg6 27. Rxe4 Nxd4 28. Rxd4 Rc8 29. Kd2 Rc7 $11 {and the draw is inevitable.}) 7... Be6 {The main move, initiating some confrontation in the centre.} ({A relatively safe option is} 7... c5 8. Bxc4 cxd4 9. Nxd4 Bd7 {[%cal Gb8c6]}) 8. Ng5 ({Dubious is} 8. e4 $6 c6 {[%cal Gb7b5] and Black is keeping the extra pawn and stays better.}) 8... Bd5 9. e4 ({I am not sure whether White is doing well after the tricky move order} 9. Nxd5 $6 Nxd5 10. Bxc4 Nxf4 11. Qf3 $5 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gc4f7,Gf3f7] Black, in his turn, has the solid reaction} e6 12. Qxf4 c5 $1 13. dxc5 Qa5+ 14. Ke2 Nd7 $11 {[%csl Rc4,Gg7][%cal Gd7c5,Gg7b2] with promising play.}) 9... h6 {The next move sequence is forced.} 10. exd5 hxg5 11. Bxg5 Nxd5 12. Bxc4 {Everything else is just worse:} ({The assault} 12. h4 $6 Nb6 $1 {[%cal Gd8d4]} 13. Be3 ({here too, the alternatives are not encouraging -} 13. h5 Qxd4 $15) ({or} 13. d5 Qd6 14. h5 e6 $15) 13... Nc6 14. h5 Bxd4 15. hxg6 {is easily neutralized by several exchanges -} Bxc3+ 16. Rxc3 Qxd1+ 17. Kxd1 Rad8+ 18. Kc1 fxg6 19. Bxc4+ Nxc4 20. Rxc4 Rf5 $17 {and Black is just a pawn up.}) ({Black is better after} 12. Qf3 $6 Nb6 13. Qxb7 Qd7 {[%cal Gb8c6]} 14. Qe4 Nc6 $15 {either.}) 12... Nb6 13. Bb3 Qxd4 $5 {A relatively new approach, which equalizes very easily.} ({The main theory is} 13... Nc6 14. d5 Nd4 {, which must be sufficient as well.}) 14. Qxd4 Bxd4 15. Nb5 Bxb2 16. Rc2 {The only reasonable try for White.} ({Black is doing well after} 16. Rxc7 Nc6 {, as follows:} 17. O-O (17. Rxb7 Na5 $1 {This move gives Black some hope for more than just a draw.} ({very dry is the position after} 17... Rab8 18. Rxb8 Rxb8 19. O-O a6 20. Rb1 Be5 $11 {L'Ami - Bok, Playchess.com INT, 2016}) 18. Rxe7 Nxb3 19. axb3 a6 20. Nc7 Rac8 {[%csl Rc7] and White has some headaches with his hanging pieces -} 21. Ke2 Ba3 22. b4 $1 {Strictly the only move to prevent material losses.} Bxb4 23. Re4 a5 $15 {[%csl Ga5,Gb4] Black can rely on this strong passed pawn, even though the situation is approximately equal}) 17... e6 18. Rxb7 Na5 $1 {A strong forcing move!} 19. Rxa7 Rxa7 20. Nxa7 Ra8 21. Rb1 ({more adventurous is} 21. Nb5 Nxb3 {[%cal Ga8a5]} 22. Be3 $1 {- the only move to keep the balance, otherwise Ra8-a5 was coming -} Rxa2 23. Bxb6 $11) (21. Be3 Nbc4 22. Nb5 Rb8 23. Bxc4 Nxc4 24. a4 Ra8 25. Ba7 Na3 $11 {and the a-pawn is falling}) 21... Bg7 22. Bd1 Nac4 23. Nc6 Rxa2 $11 {with full equality as well.}) 16... Be5 17. f4 $1 {The point of White's previous move.} ({Harmless is} 17. Nxc7 Bxc7 18. Rxc7 Nc6 19. Rxb7 ({or} 19. h4 Rfc8 20. Rxb7 e6 21. O-O Na5 22. Re7 Nc6 $11 {with a forced draw in Toma - Balabolov, ICCF email, 2019.}) 19... e6 20. Rc7 Nd4 21. Bd1 ({Or} 21. h4 Nxb3 22. axb3 Nd5 23. Rc4 Rfb8 24. Rh3 a5 $11 {[%csl Gd5] - Nd5 controls many important squares}) 21... Nd5 22. Rc4 e5 23. h4 Rfc8 24. Rxc8+ Rxc8 $11 {Dreev - Sarana, Yaroslavl, 2019.}) 17... Bd6 $146 {An important improvement.} ({An inferior alternative is} 17... c6 18. fxe5 cxb5 19. Bxe7 Re8 {because of} 20. Rc7 $1 ({Little is promised by} 20. Bf6 N8d7 21. O-O Nxf6 22. Rxf6 Nc4 23. Bxc4 bxc4 24. Rxc4 Rxe5 {with an easy draw in L'Ami - Bok, Amstelveen, 2016, for instance} 25. Rc7 Rf8 26. Rxb7 Ra5 $11) 20... N8d7 21. Bd6 Rad8 22. O-O Nc4 23. h3 $14 {White has the initiative.}) 18. Nxc7 ({The alternatives are:} 18. f5 gxf5 19. O-O ({if} 19. g4 {, then strong is} f4 $1 20. Nxc7 Bxc7 21. Rxc7 Rc8 22. Rxc8+ Nxc8 23. Kf2 Nc6 24. Bxf4 Nb6 $11 {[%cal Ga8d8,Gc6d4] and White has compensation, but hardly anything more.}) 19... Nc6 20. Nxd6 cxd6 21. Rc3 {[%cal Gc3g3]} Nd4 22. Rh3 Kg7 23. Bxe7 Rfe8 24. Rg3+ Kh7 $11 {with perpetual check.}) (18. O-O Nc6 $11) 18... Bxc7 19. Rxc7 e6 20. O-O Na6 21. Rc3 ({After} 21. Rxb7 Nc5 {the playing initiative can easily pass to the opponent, White is therefore needing his light-squared bishop.}) 21... Kg7 22. g4 {White has some pressure, but it seems that Black has enough counterplay.} Rfc8 23. Rh3 Rh8 24. Rxh8 Rxh8 25. f5 f6 26. Be3 exf5 27. gxf5 Re8 28. Bd4 Re4 $11 {I believe the draw is very likely here.} *

