on}) (9. e3 Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 Qa5 $11 {is very similar to the line with 9.Nf3}) 9... Qc7 ({good is also} 9... Qa5) 10. e3 Bxc3+ 11. Qxc3 Qxc3+ 12. bxc3 O-O {[%cal Gf8c8] Black has no problems, for example} 13. Nf3 ({or} 13. Rb1 Be4 14. Rb4 Bd5 $11) 13... Rc8 14. c4 Nd7 {[%cal Gd7b6]} 15. Nd4 Rab8 16. f3 Ba6 $11 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gd7e5]}) (7. dxc5 {is the other critical line. After} Nd7 {White has plenty of options.} 8. e3 (8. Qa4 Qc7 $1 (8... O-O $6 9. Qa3) 9. Rc1 (9. Ne4 Bxb2 10. Rb1 Bg7 {[%csl Rc5,Re1][%cal Ge8g8] was seen in Wang Hao - Topalov, London, 2012. Black has compensation even after the overprotection of the c-pawn by} 11. Rc1 O-O 12. Qa3 {, for instance} Ne5 13. e3 e6 14. d6 Qc6 15. Qb4 Bd7 $132 {It is notable that the whole White's kingside is still undeveloped!}) 9... Qxc5 (9... O-O $6 10. Nb5 Qe5 11. Qa3) 10. e4 (10. Nf3 O-O 11. e3 Nb6 $11) 10... O-O 11. Nf3 Ne5 $1 {The key to counterplay - Black does not mind the exchange of the knight in order to use the bishops and the rooks along the c-file to their utmost, as shown by:} 12. Be2 (12. Nxe5 Bxe5 13. Be2 Qd6 14. g3 (14. h3 a6 15. O-O Qf6 $15 {[%cal Gf6f4]}) 14... Bh3 $44 {[%csl Ge5,Gh3]}) 12... Bd7 13. Qd1 (13. Qb3 Rfc8 14. O-O a5 $44 {[%cal Ga5a4]}) 13... Qb4 14. Qd2 (14. Rb1 Nxf3+ 15. Bxf3 b5 16. O-O Bxc3 17. bxc3 Qxc3 $11) 14... Nxf3+ 15. Bxf3 Rfc8 16. O-O Rc7 $44) (8. e4 O-O $1 {An important move order.} ({Black should refrain from} 8... Nxc5 $2 {because of} 9. Bb5+ Kf8 10. Qd2 Qb6 11. Nge2 $16 {White is clearly better}) 9. Nf3 ({after} 9. Bd3 Nxc5 10. Nge2 e6 11. O-O exd5 12. exd5 Qb6 $44 {Black had fantastic compensation in Gupta - Negi, New Delhi, 2012.}) (9. f4 {is not a big improvement because of} Bxc3+ $1 10. bxc3 Nxc5 11. Qd4 Qa5 12. Rd1 Bd7 $44 {[%csl Ra2,Rc3][%cal Gf8c8] , when Black has enough counterplay}) (9. Bc4 Nxc5 10. Nge2 Bg4 $5 {Probably the easiest way to equalize - White will not be willing to expose the a7-g1 diagonal by 11.f3 and must agree to take on c3 with a pawn, which will