nd a pleasant strike to execute!} 11. a3 (11. bxc5 Qa5 12. Qd3 Bxc3+ {leads to a forced draw after} 13. Rxc3 Rb1+ 14. Qxb1 Qxc3+ 15. Kd1 Qd4+ 16. Ke1 (16. Qd3 $6 Qa1+) 16... Qc3+ $11 {with a logical perpetual check}) 11... O-O 12. e3 ({quite similar is} 12. Nf3 Bxc3+ 13. Rxc3 Ne4 14. Rxc6 Bb7 15. Rc2 a5 $1 {Very strong and consequent, White is well-advised to concentrate on the safety of the king -} 16. e3 axb4 17. axb4 Qd6 {[%csl Rb4,Rd5]} 18. Bd3 Qxb4+ 19. Nd2 Nxd2 20. Qxd2 Qxd2+ 21. Kxd2 Bxd5 $11) 12... Bxc3+ 13. Rxc3 Ne4 14. Rxc6 a5 $1 (14... Bb7 $143 15. Rc1) 15. Qd4 axb4 16. axb4 Nf6 $1 {[%cal Gf6d5]} 17. Nf3 ({a necessity; the mistake} 17. e4 $2 {in Muckle - Schmider, Willingen, 2019, could be punished by} e5 $1 $17) 17... Nxd5 $11) (8. Rc1 Nxc5 9. g3 O-O 10. Bg2 {looks solid, but White has yet to decide about Ng1.} Qb6 11. Qd2 Rd8 {[%cal Gc8f5] Black's pieces are very active.} 12. h4 {The latest try.} ({Black has excellent play after} 12. Nf3 Bf5 $11 {[%cal Gc5e4]}) ({in reply to} 12. Nh3 {the forcing} Bxh3 13. Bxh3 Bxc3 14. bxc3 Ne4 {seems to equalize, for example} 15. Qd4 ({or} 15. Qf4 f5 16. Bg2 Rac8 17. Bxe4 Rc4 $44 {[%cal Gc4e4] / =}) 15... Nf6 16. Qxb6 axb6 $11 {[%csl Ra2,Rd5]}) 12... Bf5 13. Nh3 Bxc3 14. bxc3 Be4 $1 15. Bxe4 Nxe4 {In the only known game White continued with} 16. Qf4 (16. Qd3 Nc5 17. Qc4 {is too artificial, then} e6 $5 18. dxe6 $140 Nxe6 {is just one of the promising options -} 19. O-O Rac8 {[%csl Ra2,Rc3][%cal Gd8d2] with huge compensation}) 16... Qb2 $1 {[%csl Rc1,Rc3]} 17. c4 Rac8 18. Kf1 Rxd5 $1 (18... Nc3 {, which would have been the refutation of White's castling, is parried here by} 19. Re1) 19. Kg2 Rd4 20. Qe5 Qb6 $11 {and Black had no problems in Krasenkow - Kosakowski, Bydgoszcz, 2022.}) (8. Nf3 O-O {will surely transpose to another line like the ones with 9.e3 or 9.e4}) 8... O-O $1 {The remark to 8.e4 is absolutely valid here as well -} (8... Nxc5 $6 {is premature because of} 9. Bb5+) 9. Bc4 (9. Nf3 Nxc5 10. Nd4 (10. Be2 Qb6 11. Qc1 Bf5 $11 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gc5e4]}) 10... Qa5 $1 11. Bb5 {The idea is to lure the pawn to the a6-square.} (11. Be2 Ne4 12. Bf3 Nxc3 13. Qd2 Bxd4 $5 14. exd4 b6 15. Qxc3 (15. bxc3 $143 $6 Ba6) 15... Qa6 $1 {This is the equalizer, based on} 16. d6 $5 (16. Be2 Qa4 17. O-O Bb7 $11) 16... exd6 $1 17. Bxa8 Re8+ 18. Kd2 Qe2+ 19. Kc1 Qxf2 20. Qg3 ({the draw is unavoidable after} 20. Qc2 Re1+ 21. Rxe1 Qxe1+ 22. Qd1 Qe3+ 23. Qd2 Qg1+ $11) 20... Qxd4 21. Rd1 Qc5+ 22. Qc3 Qg5+ 23. Qd2 Qc5+ $11 {with an original perpetual check}) (11. Rc1 Bd7 {[%cal Gc5a4,Gf8c8] Black has an easy game -} 12. Bd3 (12. Be2 Ne4 $132) (12. Nb3 {is the other way to prevent 12...Ne4, but after} Nxb3 13. Qxb3 Rac8 14. Be2 Rc7 {[%cal Gf8c8]} 15. O-O Rfc8 $15 {White has to be careful}) 12... b5 $5 {A highly ambitious attempt.} ({Black, if he wishes so, can force a draw by playing} 12... Na4 13. Qb3 Nc5 14. Qc2 Na4 $11) 13. a3 b4 14. axb4 Qxb4 $132 {/=}) (11. Bc4 Qb4 12. Bb3 Bd7 $5 13. O-O a5 $44 {[%cal Ga5a4]}) 11... a6 12. Be2 Ne4 13. Bf3 Nxc3 14. Qd2 Bd7 15. Qxc3 ({after} 15. bxc3 Bb5 $1 {would be rather unpleasant to meet}) 15... Qxc3+ 16. bxc3 Rac8 17. Kd2 b5 18. Rhc1 Rfd8 $44 {[%csl Ra2,Rc3,Gd7,Gf6][%cal Gc8c5] Black has a very comfortable compensation for the pawn.}) 9... Nxc5 10. Nge2 Qa5 $1 {Here White's e-pawn is not hanging, so the compensation has to be proved in a different manner:} 11. Qd2 (11. O-O Qb4 12. Bb3 Rd8 $5 {This is just one of the many good moves, such as} (12... a5) ({and} 12... Bf5) 13. Rb1 (13. Nd4 Bxd4 14. exd4 Nxb3 15. axb3 b5 16. Re1 Bb7 $11 {[%csl Rd5]}) 13... Nxb3 14. Qxb3 Qxb3 15. axb3 Rd6 {[%cal Gd6b6]} ({equally good is} 15... b5 16. Rfd1 Bb7 $44) 16. Rfd1 Rb6 17. Ne4 Bg7 18. Nd4 Bxd4 19. Rxd4 Bf5 $11 {L. Schmidt - T. Tomizawa, ICCF email, 2019}) (11. a3 Ne4 $132 12. O-O Nxc3 13. Nxc3 Bxc3 14. bxc3 Qxc3 15. Qa4 (15. Qe2 Bd7 16. Rfc1 Qe5 17. Rab1 Rab8 $11) 15... Bf5 16. Rac1 Qe5 $11) (11. Rb1 $6 {[%cal Gb2b4] creates a threat, which can be ignored -} Bf5 $1 12. b4 Qb6 13. bxc5 Qxc5 {[%csl Rb1,Rc3,Rc4]} 14. Rxb7 Qxc4 15. Qb3 Qa6 $15) 11... b5 $1 12. Nxb5 ({of course not} 12. Bxb5 $2 {because of} Nb3 $1 $17) 12... Qxd2+ 13. Kxd2 Ne4+ $1 {I like this move, for it keeps White's rook on its initial h1-square.} (13... Rb8 $5 {is also good}) 14. Ke1 Ba6 15. f3 ({wrong is} 15. Rb1 $2 Rfc8 16. Bd3 Nc5 17. Bc4 Rab8 $17 {and Black was much better in Mamedyarov - Vachier Lagrave, Berlin, 2015}) (15. Nd6 exd6 16. Bxa6 Nc5 17. Bc4 Bxb2 18. Rb1 Rab8 $11 {[%csl Gb2,Gc5][%cal Gb8b4] I don't think Black has any problems here.}) 15... Bxb5 (15... Rac8 $5) 16. Bxb5 Rab8 17. fxe4 (17. Bc6 Bxb2 18. Rd1 Nc3 $11) 17... Rxb5 18. Rb1 Rfb8 19. b3 Ra5 20. Kf2 Rxa2 21. Kf3 Be5 $11 {[%csl Ge5] with full compensation for the pawn in all the lines.}) 7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 Qb6 9. Nb3 ({Little is promised by} 9. e3 Qxb2 10. Rc1 (10. Bb5+ $143 $6 Nd7 11. Rc1 Bxd4 $1 12. exd4 O-O 13. O-O Nf6 $15) 10... O-O 11. Bc4 Qb4 ({strong enough is} 11... Bxd4 12. exd4 Bf5 13. O-O Rc8 $11) 12. Qb3 Qxb3 13. Bxb3 Na6 $11 {Black is fine.}) 9... a5 $5 {[%cal Ga5a4] A rare move, which is easily equalizing in my opinion.} ({The main theory is concentrated on} 9... O-O 10. e3 Rd8) 10. e3 (10. a4 O-O ({a plausible alternative is} 10... Bd7 $5 11. e3 Qb4 12. Qc2 Bf5 13. Qd1 O-O $11) 11. g3 ({if} 11. e3 {, then} Bg4 $1) 11... Na6 12. Bg2 Bd7 13. O-O Rac8 $11 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Gf6c3] and Black has a very pleasant play.}) (10. Rc1 O-O 11. e3 a4 12. Nd4 Qxb2 13. Bd3 Bxd4 14. exd4 Nd7 {is absolutely acceptable for Black. Perhaps White's best is to force a draw by repetition with} 15. Nb5 Nf6 16. Rb1 Qxa2 17. Nc3 Qa3 18. Nb5 Qa2 $11) (10. Qc2 O-O 11. e3 Na6 $44 {[%cal Ga6b4]}) (10. Nd2 $5 $146 {An interesting idea, but not enough for obtaining an advantage.} Qxb2 $1 {Black must enter the complications, for} (10... O-O {is most probably insufficient for equality after} 11. Rb1 $14) 11. Rb1 Qxc3 12. Rc1 Qa3 13. Rxc8+ Kd7 14. Rc2 {and here comes the key move} Rc8 $1 (14... Na6 $143 $6 15. e3 $14 {[%cal Gf1b5]}) 15. e3 (15. Rxc8 Kxc8 16. g3 Nd7 17. Bg2 Kd8 {is similar -} 18. O-O Qxa2 $5 (18... Rc8 {may transpose}) 19. Ne4 Rc8 20. d6 Rc2 $132) 15... Rxc2 16. Qxc2 Kd8 {[%cal Gb8d7]} 17. Be2 Nd7 18. O-O Qc5 19. Qe4 Qb4 $11 {looks quite safe for Black.}) 10... a4 11. Bb5+ (11. Nd4 Qxb2 12. Rc1 {transposes to 10.î Rc1.}) 11... Bd7 12. Nd4 O-O $5 $146 {An attempt at refining the move order.} ({The practice has seen} 12... Bxd4 13. Qxd4 Qxd4 14. exd4 Bxb5 15. Nxb5 Ra5 16. Rc1 O-O {Bluebaum - Swiercz, Moscow, 2016, when White could try} 17. Nc3 Nd7 18. Kd2 Nf6 19. d6 exd6 20. f3 Rb8 $11 {Still, the endgame is about equal.}) 13. O-O ({An important alternative is} 13. Rb1 Rc8 14. O-O (14. Bxa4 {does not win a second pawn - after} Bxa4 15. Nxa4 Qb4+ 16. Nc3 Rxa2 17. Qd2 Ra5 {Black has great compensation, for example} 18. Nde2 Nd7 19. O-O Ne5 20. Qc2 Nc4 $44) 14... Bxd4 15. Qxd4 (15. Bxd7 Nxd7 16. exd4 Nf6 $11) 15... Qxd4 16. exd4 {and these doubled pawns are needing protection -} Bxb5 17. Nxb5 Ra5 18. Nc3 Nd7 19. Rfe1 Kf8 $11 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gd7f6]}) ({White may insert} 13. Bxd7 Nxd7 {before} ({worth checking is the intermediate} 13... Qxb2 $5) 14. Rb1 {, when} Bxd4 {is likely to transpose after the exemplary sequence} 15. Qxd4 Qxd4 16. exd4 Nf6 $11 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gf8d8]}) 13... Bxd4 14. Qxd4 Qxd4 15. exd4 Bxb5 16. Nxb5 Ra5 17. Nc3 Rc8 18. Rfe1 ({Or} 18. Rfc1 Nd7 {, reaching almost the same position as in the note for 13.Rb1.}) 18... Kf8 $11 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gd7f6,Gd7b6] Black is simply not worse.} *

