xd5 10. e3 O-O 11. h3 c6 12. Bd3 Be6 (12... Nd7 13. O-O a5 $11) 13. O-O Nd7 $11) ({The extravagant} 6. h4 $6 {is inviting an adequate reaction - firstly, eliminating the bishop by} Nxg5 $1 7. hxg5 {, then opening the position for the pair of bishops with} dxc4 8. e3 (8. e4 Bg4 $15) (8. Qa4+ c6 $1 9. Qxc4 Qb6 10. O-O-O Be6 11. Qa4 O-O $15) 8... Be6 $5 9. Be2 c5 10. O-O Nd7 $15 11. d5 $140 Bg4) (6. Bh4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 dxc4 {leads us to yet another opening tabiya:} 8. Qa4+ (8. e3 b5 $1 9. a4 (9. Be2 Nd7 10. a4 c6 {- see 10.?e2 below}) 9... c6 10. Qb1 (10. Nd2 a6 11. Be2 Ra7 12. O-O O-O $15 {[%cal Gb8d7]}) (10. Be2 Nd7 11. O-O Nb6 $15) 10... a6 11. Be2 Nd7 12. O-O Nb6 13. Ne5 Bxe5 14. dxe5 Nxa4 {with arguable compensation, Nakamura - Aronian, Saint Louis, 2014, for instance} 15. Bxc4 Qc7 $17) (8. e4 b5 9. a4 c6 10. Be2 Nd7 11. O-O a6 12. Qd2 O-O 13. Rfd1 Bb7 $15) 8... c6 $5 ({a sound alternative is} 8... Qd7 9. Qxc4 b6 {[%cal Gc8a6]}) 9. Qxc4 Qa5 {and Black is fine in the view of the coming 10...?e6, as shown by:} 10. e3 (10. e4 Be6 11. Qd3 Nd7 {[%cal Gd7c5]} 12. Nd2 (12. Be2 $2 Nc5 $1 13. Qe3 Nxe4 $1 $17) 12... b5 $5 (12... Rd8) 13. Be2 b4 $15 {[%csl Rc3,Rd4][%cal Gg7a1]}) 10... Be6 11. Qb4 (11. Qd3 $6 {does not bring the queen in safety, as demonstrated by} Nd7 12. Nd2 Nc5 $1 {and Black has the playing initiative -} 13. Qc2 (13. dxc5 Rd8 14. Qc2 Bf5 15. e4 Bxc3 16. Rd1 Bxe4 17. Qxe4 Bxd2+ 18. Ke2 Qb5+ 19. Kf3 Qxc5 20. Bd3 Qh5+ 21. g4 Qxh4 22. Rxd2 h5 $15) 13... Bf5 14. Nb3 Nxb3 (14... Qa3 15. Qc1) 15. Qxb3 e5 16. Bc4 O-O 17. O-O b5 $15) 11... Qxb4 12. cxb4 Nd7 {is approximately equal:} 13. Bd3 (13. Be2 a5 $5 (13... Bd5 $11) 14. b5 c5 15. O-O a4 16. Rfc1 Rc8 $11) 13... Bd5 $5 {[%cal Ge7e5]} ({the b4-pawn is a target and Black's hidden resources are revealed by the exciting line} 13... a5 14. b5 Nc5 15. Bc2 cxb5 16. Rb1 b4 $1 17. dxc5 Bxa2 18. Ba4+ Kf8 19. Rc1 b3 $132) 14. e4 (14. O-O e5) 14... Be6 15. h3 Rd8 16. Kd2 Nb6 $132) 6... O-O $5 ({More flexible than} 6... Nxc3 7. bxc3 c5) 7. Nxd5 {Taking the bull by the horns.} ({Another very entertaining idea from Black can be seen after} 7. e3 c5 8. cxd5 Bf5 $1 $132 {Regarding the mentioned example, the immediate} 9. Qb3 $146 {is naturally coming to mind, after} (9. Bc4 cxd4 10. exd4 Nd7 {[%cal Gd7b6]} 11. O-O Nb6 12. Bb3 Nxc3 13. bxc3 Nxd5 14. Bd2 Rc8 15. Rc1 ({Breaking the blockade with} 15. c4 {makes more sense -} Nc7 16. Be3 b5 $11) 15... Bd3 16. Re1 Bc4 17. Ne5 b5 $11) (9. Be2 cxd4 10. Nxd4 (10. exd4 Nxc3 11. bxc3 Qxd5 12. O-O Nc6 $11 {[%cal Ga8c8]}) 10... Nxc3 11. bxc3 Be4 12. O-O (12. c4 Bxg2 13. Rg1 Bh3 14. Rg3 Bc8 $132) 12... Bxd5 13. Bg3 Nc6 $11 {Moiseenko - Heimann, Germany, 2017}) (9. Bd3 Nxc3 10. bxc3 Qxd5 11. O-O Nc6 12. Bxf5 Qxf5 13. Qb1 (13. Rb1 b6 14. Qa4 Rac8 15. Rfd1 Rfd8 $11) 13... Qxb1 (13... b6 14. Qxf5 gxf5 15. Rab1 cxd4 16. Nxd4 $14 {Thybo - Ragger, Germany, 2022}) 14. Raxb1 Na5 ({a slightly different version of this typical for the featured opening pawn sacrifice is} 14... b6 $5 15. dxc5 $140 Rfc8 $44) 15. Rb5 b6 16. dxc5 Rfc8 17. cxb6 axb6 18. Rxb6 Nc4 $44 19. Rb7 e5 20. Bg3 Rxa2 21. Rd1 f6 {[%csl Rg3]} 22. h3 Bf8 $11) (9. Be5 Nxc3 10. bxc3 Qxd5 11. Qb3 Qxb3 12. axb3 cxd4 ({a logical exchange, while} 12... Rd8 $5 {may soon transpose}) 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. exd4 (14. Nxd4 Nd7 $11) 14... Nd7 15. Kd2 Rfd8 16. Bd3 Bxd3 17. Kxd3 e5 18. Rhe1 exd4 19. Nxd4 a6 20. Kc2 Rac8 $11 {So - Vachier Lagrave, Berlin, 2022}) 9... cxd4 {White can choose from:} 10. Nxd4 (10. exd4 Nxc3 11. bxc3 Be4 {and now:} 12. c4 (12. Bc4 Bxf3 13. gxf3 {White's pawn structure is in ruins, which also means an eternal problem with the safety of the king. No wonder that the opponent will be striving at reaching its residence, starting with} Nd7 14. Qxb7 Rc8 15. Bb5 Nb6 16. Bc6 {and here comes the magnificent blow} e5 $1 17. dxe5 (17. Bxe5 Bxe5 18. dxe5 Qg5 19. Kf1 Qxe5 $44 {/=}) 17... Qh4 18. Qxa7 (18. Bg3 $2 Qc4 $17) 18... Qxf4 19. Qxb6 Qxf3 20. O-O Qg4+ $11) 12... e6 $5 (12... Bxf3 13. Qxf3 Bxd4 14. Rd1 Qa5+ 15. Bd2 Qxa2 16. Be2 Na6 17. h4 Nc5 18. Kf1 $13) 13. Be2 (13. Qxb7 $143 $6 Bxf3 14. gxf3 Nd7 15. Rd1 e5 $15 {[%csl Re1]}) 13... exd5 14. Qxb7 Qb6 15. Qxb6 (15. Qxa8 Bxf3 16. Bxf3 Nc6 17. c5 Qa6 18. Be2 Qa5+ 19. Bd2 Qc7 20. Bf4 Qa5+ $11) 15... axb6 16. cxd5 (16. O-O Nc6 $11) 16... Bxd5 17. O-O Nc6 $11) 10... Nxc3 11. bxc3 (11. Nxf5 gxf5 12. bxc3 Nd7 13. Be2 Nc5 14. Qa3 Ne4 $11) 11... Be4 12. Bc4 Nd7 13. f3 Nc5 14. Qb5 Bxd5 15. Qxc5 Bxc4 16. Qxc4 e5 {The point of the entire operation - Black is winning the piece back and seems to be in order, for example} 17. Bg3 (17. Ne6 $6 Qc8 $1 18. Qxc8 Rfxc8 19. Nxg7 exf4 $13) (17. Bxe5 Bxe5 18. Kf2 Rc8 19. Qb3 a6 $44) 17... Rc8 18. Qd3 exd4 19. cxd4 Re8 20. Kf2 (20. O-O $2 Rxe3 $1 $19) 20... Bh6 21. f4 (21. Rhe1 Qa5 {[%cal Gc8c3]} 22. a4 Rc3 23. Qb5 Rc2+ 24. Kf1 Qd2 25. Qe2 Qxe2+ 26. Rxe2 Rxe2 27. Kxe2 Rxe3+ 28. Kf1 Rd3 $11) 21... Qa5 {[%cal Gc8c3]} 22. Rhc1 Rxc1 23. Rxc1 Qxa2+ 24. Kf3 Qd5+ 25. e4 Qh5+ 26. Kf2 Qg4 27. h3 Qe6 28. Re1 f5 29. e5 Qd5 $132) (7. cxd5 Nxc3 8. bxc3 Qxd5 9. e3 Qa5 $1 10. Qd2 Nd7 $1 {[%cal Ge7e5] A very subtle idea - Black is making use of f4-bishop by preparing, alongside with 11...c5, the central break e7-e5:} 11. Rb1 (11. Bd3 $6 e5 12. Bg3 Re8 13. e4 exd4 (13... b6 14. Rd1 Ba6 $15 {Wang - Grischuk, Beijing, 2014}) 14. cxd4 Qxd2+ 15. Kxd2 c5 16. d5 c4 17. Bc2 Nc5 18. e5 Bg4 $17) (11. c4 Qxd2+ 12. Kxd2 c5 13. Bd3 cxd4 14. exd4 Nb6 15. a4 Be6 16. Rhc1 Rac8 17. c5 Nd5 18. Be3 b6 $11) 11... c6 12. c4 (12. Be2 $6 e5 $15) 12... Qxd2+ 13. Kxd2 Re8 14. Be2 {So far Gavrilov - Gordievsky, Kolomna, 2016, when} e5 $11 {is consistent.}) 7... c5 8. Qc2 ({The danger in front of White is well described by} 8. Nc3 $2 Qa5 9. e3 Nc6 10. Rc1 {, which took place in the high-level game Gelfand - Grischuk, Sochi, 2014. Black could continue with} cxd4 11. exd4 Rd8 12. Be3 Bxd4 $1 13. Bxd4 $140 Nxc3 14. bxc3 Bg4 15. Qd2 Bxf3 16. gxf3 e5 $17) (8. e3 cxd4 9. exd4 (9. Bd3 Nd6 {is likely to transpose}) 9... Nc6 10. Bd3 (10. Be2 Bf5 11. O-O e6 12. Ne3 Nxd4 13. Nxd4 Bxd4 $11) 10... Nd6 11. O-O Bg4 {and Black will regain the d4-pawn at once or after} 12. Re1 Rc8 13. Rc1 Re8 $11 {[%csl Rd4]}) ({The curious move order} 8. Bc7 $5 Qd7 9. Be5 (9. Ne5 $6 Qe8) 9... f6 10. Bxb8 Rxb8 {is worth attention - White has provoked f7-f6 but at the cost of the valuable dark-squared bishop. On a general basis, its absence should yield Black enough compensation for the pawn and the sample variations seem to confirm this:} 11. e3 (11. Qc2 f5 12. e3 cxd4 13. exd4 b6 14. Be2 Bb7 15. O-O e6 16. Nc3 (16. Ne3 g5 $132) 16... Nxc3 17. bxc3 Rfc8 18. Rae1 Bxf3 19. Bxf3 Rxc4 20. Qb3 Rbc8 21. Re3 f4 22. Be2 (22. Rd3 Bf6 $11) 22... R4c6 23. Rf3 Qd5 $11) 11... f5 12. Bd3 (12. Nc3 cxd4 13. exd4 Nxc3 14. bxc3 Qc7 15. Be2 Be6 $11 {[%csl Rc4]} 16. c5 b6) 12... b5 $1 13. O-O e6 14. Nf4 (14. Nc3 cxd4 15. exd4 bxc4 16. Bxe4 fxe4 17. Ne5 Qc7 $11) 14... cxd4 15. exd4 Qd6 {[%csl Rf4]} 16. Qc1 Bh6 17. g3 bxc4 18. Bxc4 g5 19. Ne2 Bb7 $132) ({In reply to} 8. Be5 {Black has the extra opportunity for} Nc6 $5 9. Bxg7 Qa5+ 10. Nd2 $140 (10. b4 $2 Nxb4 $17) 10... Kxg7 11. dxc5 e6 12. b4 Nxb4 13. Nxb4 Qxb4 14. Rb1 Qc3 15. Rb3 Qa5 16. Rb5 Qc3 $11) 8... e6 $1 $146 {In connection with the next strike - a stunning tactical solution.} ({Supporting Ne4 with} 8... f5 {is another way to prove enough counterplay.}) 9. Nc7 {The principled reply.} ({Less challenging is} 9. Nc3 Nxc3 10. bxc3 {, when} Nc6 11. e3 Qa5 {[%csl Re1][%cal Gc5d4,Ga5e1] is the key to sufficient counterplay. White cannot keep the central pawns intact, so the greedy} 12. Bd6 {is probably the best, even though Black can claim attractive compensation by means of} cxd4 $5 (12... Rd8 {is also quite playable -} 13. Bxc5 b6 14. Bb4 Nxb4 15. cxb4 Qxb4+ 16. Qd2 Qa4 17. Be2 e5 18. O-O exd4 19. Nxd4 Be6 $11) 13. Bxf8 Kxf8 14. exd4 Nxd4 15. Nxd4 Bxd4 16. Rc1 Bd7 $132 {[%csl Gd4,Gd7]}) ({Black has typical compensation after} 9. Qxe4 exd5 10. Qxd5 Qb6 {, as demonstrated by} 11. Qxc5 Qxb2 12. Rc1 Nc6 13. Qb5 Nxd4 14. Qxb2 Nxf3+ 15. gxf3 Bxb2 16. Rc2 Ba3 17. e4 Bd7 $44 {/=}) 9... e5 $1 10. Qxe4 {The relatively best of all the possible captures:} (10. Nxa8 $6 exf4 11. Qxe4 Qa5+ 12. Nd2 (12. Kd1 Rd8 $40) 12... Nc6 13. Rd1 Bf5 14. Qxf4 Nxd4 15. e3 Ne6 16. Qf3 Rd8 $17 {[%csl Re1][%cal Ga5e1,Gg7b2]}) (10. dxe5 $6 Qxc7 11. Qxe4 Bf5 12. Qe3 Nc6 13. a3 Rad8 $17 {[%csl Re1]}) (10. Bxe5 Bxe5 11. dxe5 (11. Nxa8 $6 Qa5+ 12. Nd2 Nxd2 13. Qxd2 Qxd2+ 14. Kxd2 cxd4 $17) 11... Qxc7 12. Qxe4 Nc6 $132 {A critical position, in spite of being two pawns down, Black has a promising compensation. For instance, after} 13. O-O-O Qa5 (13... Nb4 14. Qb1 Bf5 $5 15. e4 Bg4 16. a3 Nc6 17. Rd5 Be6 $13) 14. a3 Bf5 15. Qf4 Rad8 16. Rxd8 Rxd8 17. e4 {Black has once again two reliable continuations -} Nb4 $5 (17... Qa4 18. Be2 Be6 $11 {[%csl Rc4]}) 18. Be2 Na2+ 19. Kb1 (19. Kc2 Qa4+) 19... Nc3+ 20. bxc3 Qxa3 21. Nd2 Bxe4+ 22. Nxe4 Qb3+ 23. Kc1 Qa3+ $11) 10... Qxc7 (10... exf4 $2 11. Qxf4 $18) 11. Bxe5 Qa5+ 12. Kd1 (12. Nd2 Bh6 $1 (12... Re8 $5 {is a possible alternative, but the text is stronger, especially when 13.e3?! is running into a different way to attack e5-bishop, namely 13...Nc6!}) 13. Qc2 (13. Bf4 Bf5 14. Qf3 Bxf4 15. Qxf4 Nc6 $1 {is about to lead to an exciting perpetual after} 16. e4 $1 Bxe4 17. O-O-O f5 18. f3 Nb4 $1 19. fxe4 Qa4 20. Nb3 Nxa2+ 21. Kc2 Nb4+ $11) (13. Qd3 Nc6 14. Qc3 {- 13.Qc2.}) 13... Nc6 14. Qc3 Qd8 15. d5 Nxe5 16. Qxe5 Bg7 {It is time to go back to the normal working diagonal, Black has ample compensation -} 17. Qg3 Bxb2 18. Rb1 (18. Rd1 Qa5) 18... Bd4 $1 19. Qb3 (19. e3 $6 Bc3) 19... Bf5 20. Rc1 Re8 21. e3 Qb6 $132) 12... Bf5 $1 13. Qxb7 Bxe5 14. Nxe5 (14. dxe5 $2 Rd8+ 15. Kc1 Nd7 $19 {[%csl Rc1][%cal Ga8b8,Gd7e5]}) 14... cxd4 15. f4 {The most principled continuation compared to:} (15. Qxa8 $6 Qxe5 16. Qd5 Qf6 $40 {[%csl Rd1][%cal Gb8c6,Gf8d8]}) (15. Qd5 Qb4 16. b3 Bc2+ $1 ({nothing is changed by} 16... Na6 17. Nc6 {and now} Bc2+ $1 $11) 17. Kxc2 Qc3+ 18. Kb1 Qe1+ 19. Kb2 Qc3+ $11 20. Ka3 $140 Na6 $1) (15. g4 $6 Qxe5 16. gxf5 {is a gamble from White's point of view, regarding the insecure location of the king, especially after} d3 $1 17. exd3 Nd7 $1 {[%csl Rd1]} 18. Qxd7 Qxb2 19. Rc1 Rfe8 20. fxg6 hxg6 21. Qg4 Rab8 $40) 15... Qa4+ $3 {An exquisite way to justify Black's whole concept.} ({White has a considerable material advantage after} 15... Na6 $2 16. Qb5 $16) ({So is with} 15... Nd7 $2 16. Nxd7 Bxd7 17. Qxd7 Rab8 18. Qd5 Qb4 19. b3 $16) 16. b3 {This move allows a spectacular finish to the game. The alternatives can prolong it, but the terrible position of the king will be the long-term leading factor for all the general assessments.} (16. Qb3 Qe8 (16... Qa5 $11) 17. g4 Be4 18. Rg1 Nc6 19. Nxc6 Bxc6 $44) (16. Ke1 Nd7 17. Qb5 Qxb5 18. cxb5 Nxe5 19. fxe5 Rfe8 $11) 16... Qa5 $1 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Gf5c2] The right square - Black has sacrificed two tempi with a good reason.} (16... Qa3 $2 {is the wrong form of the idea for queen penetration -} 17. g4 $1 Qb2 18. Rc1 Bb1 19. Qxa8 Nd7 20. Qg2 $18) 17. Qxa8 {This capture is equivalent to a draw offer, but there is no way to prevent the imminent draw by perpetual, as shown by:} (17. Qd5 Bc2+ $1 18. Kxc2 Qc3+ 19. Kb1 Qe1+ $11) (17. g4 Bc2+ $1 18. Kxc2 Qc3+ $11) (17. Rc1 Qxa2 18. Qxa8 Qxb3+ 19. Ke1 Qe3 $11) 17... Bc2+ $1 18. Kxc2 Qc3+ 19. Kb1 Qe1+ 20. Kb2 Qc3+ $11 *

