8... Bg7 9. e4 O-O 10. Nf3 {is sensible, with mutual chances after the strike at the centre} (10. e5 $6 {is premature -} Bf5 $1 {forces the opponent to} 11. exf6 ({the retreat} 11. Qd1 $2 {will mean a complete failure of White's central strategy after} Ne4 $19) 11... Bxd3 12. fxg7 Re8 13. Bxd3 {and} e6 $1 {ruins the center. Noteworthy, Black is ready to invest in an exchange for this purpose in reply to 14.Bb5. The opening of the e-file can be prevented by giving up a second pawn -} 14. d6 Qxd6 15. Bb5 Nc6 $15 {[%cal Gc6d4]}) 10... e6 11. dxe6 Bxe6 12. Qxd8 Rxd8 13. Ng5 Nc6 14. Nxe6 fxe6 $11 {[%cal Gc6d4]}) (7. Qxb7 $6 Nc6 {is exactly what Black is aiming at -} 8. e3 Rb8 9. Qa6 Nb4 10. Qe2 c5 11. a3 (11. dxc5 Qa5 12. a3 Ne4 $17) (11. Nf3 Qa5 $17) 11... Qa5 $17) 7... c5 $1 8. d5 ({This move is provoking a powerful pawn sacrifice. Before dealing with it, let us see the course of events if White gains material at once -} 8. dxc5 Bg7 ({Black has at least three plausible options, depending mainly on the development of Nb8 -} 8... Na6 9. Qa3 Rc8 10. b4 $13) (8... Bc6 $5 9. Nf3 Bg7 {, when the d7-square is also accessible for it}) ({or} 8... Nc6 $5 9. Nf3 Qa5 {with double-edged play, as well as after the text:}) {In case of} 9. e4 (9. Nf3 O-O 10. e4 (10. Qxb7 $2 Nc6 $19 {[%csl Re1][%cal Ga8b8,Gc6b4]}) 10... Bc6 {[%csl Re4]} 11. Qc4 b5 $1 12. cxb6 axb6 13. e5 Nfd7 14. e6 Bxf3 15. gxf3 Ne5 16. Qe4 Na6 $132) ({After} 9. Qa3 O-O 10. e4 {Black can choose between the abovementioned options. Besides, there is also} Nc6 11. Nf3 Qb8 $5 {and now:} 12. Bb5 (12. Be2 b5 $1 13. Nxb5 (13. Bxb5 Nxe4 14. Bxc6 Bxc6 15. Nxe4 Bxe4 16. O-O Qb7 $11) 13... a5 $1 {[%cal Gc6b4]} 14. e5 Nxe5 15. Nc3 Bc6 $44) 12... Rd8 13. O-O Bg4 $5 14. Be2 (14. Be3 Bxf3 15. gxf3 Nd4 16. Bxd4 Rxd4 17. Rad1 Qe5 18. Rxd4 Qxd4 19. Rd1 Qe5 $44) 14... Bxf3 15. Bxf3 Nd4 16. Rb1 Qe5 $11) {I would like to suggest the sharp} 9... Qa5 $146 (9... O-O) 10. Bd2 Qxc5 11. Qxb7 (11. Be2 O-O 12. Rc1 Nc6 13. Nf3 Qb4 14. Qxb4 Nxb4 15. a3 Nc6 $11) 11... O-O {and here is the critical position for the assessment of the new idea. Black seems to be in fine shape:} 12. Rc1 {must be White's safest -} (12. Qxa8 Ng4 $1 (12... Bc6 $2 13. Be3) 13. Nd1 Bc6 $19) (12. Be3 Qa5 13. Qxa8 Ng4 $1 {[%csl Re1][%cal Gg7c3,Gg4e3]} 14. Rc1 Nxe3 15. Qb7 Bxc3+ 16. bxc3 Nxf1 17. Qb2 Nc6 18. Kxf1 Ne5 $40 {[%csl Rf1][%cal Ge5d3,Gd7b5]}) 12... Bc6 13. Qc7 (13. Qb3 Nbd7 $132 {[%cal Ga8b8,Gd7e5]}) 13... Qb4 $1 14. Bd3 Qxb2 15. Nf3 Qb6 16. Qxe7 Re8 17. Qa3 Nxe4 18. Nxe4 Bxe4 19. Bxe4 Rxe4+ 20. Be3 Nd7 21. O-O $11) 8... b5 $1 9. Nxb5 ({The complications after} 9. e4 $6 c4 $1 10. Bxc4 (10. Qc2 $6 Na6 11. Nf3 Bg7 $15) 10... bxc4 11. Qb7 Qb6 12. Qxa8 Ng4 $1 {does not definitely favour White, e. g.} 13. Nge2 (13. Nd1 $2 Bh6 14. Bxh6 Nxh6 15. Nf3 O-O 16. O-O Na6 17. Qxf8+ Kxf8 $19) 13... e5 $1 14. f3 Nf2 15. O-O Nd3+ 16. Kh1 Nxc1 17. Rfxc1 Bh6 18. d6 Bc6 19. Nd5 Bxa8 20. Nxb6 axb6 21. Rxc4 Bc6 22. Nc3 Kd7 $15) 9... Bg7 {The most obvious reply.} ({The tournament practice has seen} 9... Bxb5 $5 10. Qxb5+ Nbd7 $44 {Nakamura - Caruana, Saint Louis, 2015, though Black can keep this bishop}) (9... Na6 $5 {also deserves attention.}) 10. Nc3 O-O 11. e4 ({More cautious is} 11. e3 e6 12. dxe6 Bxe6 13. Bc4 Bf5 14. Nf3 Nc6 15. Qa4 Nb4 (15... Qc7 $5 16. O-O Rab8 $44) 16. O-O Nc2 17. Rb1 Nb4 $11) (11. Nf3 e6 $132) 11... e6 12. Bc4 (12. dxe6 Bxe6 13. Bc4 {is very similar to the note from above, the slight difference in the location of the e-pawn can provoke} Bxc4 14. Qxc4 Qd4 $1 15. Qe2 $140 Qb4 16. a3 Qb7 17. Nf3 Nc6 18. O-O Rfe8 $44 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gc6d4]}) ({The other natural developing move} 12. Nf3 {is running into a remarkable tactical operation -} exd5 13. exd5 Re8+ 14. Be2 Nxd5 $1 15. Qxd5 (15. Nxd5 Be6 $11) 15... Bxc3+ 16. bxc3 Rxe2+ 17. Kf1 Re8 18. Kg1 Be6 19. Qxd8 Rxd8 $11) 12... exd5 13. exd5 Bf5 $1 14. Nf3 ({Black's activity increases by every move, e. g.} 14. Nge2 $6 Nbd7 15. O-O Ne5 $15 {[%cal Ga8b8]}) 14... Re8+ ({In another correspondence game Black preferred the immediate} 14... Nbd7 $5 15. O-O Rb8 16. Qa3 (16. Qd1 $6 Nb6) 16... Rb4 (16... Nb6 $6 17. Ba6) (16... Ne4 $5) 17. Be2 (17. b3 Nb6 $132) 17... Qb8 18. h3 Re8 19. Rd1 Ne4 (19... Bc2 $5 20. Rd2 Be4 $44) 20. Bf1 Nd6 21. Qa5 h6 $44 {Malin - Ergenekon, ICCF email, 2019.}) 15. Be3 Nbd7 ({A sound alternative is} 15... Ng4 $5 {for eliminating the dark-squared bishop and typical counterplay -} 16. O-O Nxe3 17. fxe3 Nd7 $44) 16. O-O Rb8 17. Qa3 Rb4 $1 18. b3 Ng4 $1 19. Bxc5 ({In reply to} 19. Bd2 {Black has most probably prepared} Nde5 20. Nxe5 Bxe5 (20... Nxe5 $5 21. Be2 Rd4 22. Be3 Qh4 $44) 21. h3 Qh4 {with a huge concentration on the kingside and a likely perpetual after} 22. Rae1 Nh2 $1 ({after} 22... Bh2+ 23. Kh1 {the return of this bishop to the centre may also lead to a draw by repetition}) 23. Rxe5 Rxe5 24. Kxh2 Bxh3 25. f4 Bxg2+ 26. Kxg2 Qg4+ $11) 19... Rxc4 $1 20. bxc4 Nxc5 21. Qxc5 Bxc3 22. Rac1 Ba5 {[%cal Ga5b6]} 23. d6 Re6 24. h3 ({The endgame after} 24. Nd4 Qxd6 25. Qxd6 Rxd6 26. Nxf5 gxf5 $11 {is about equal.}) 24... Bb6 25. Qa3 Nxf2 26. c5 Nd3 27. Nd4 Nxc5 28. Rxc5 Rxd6 29. Nxf5 Rd3 30. Nh6+ Kg7 31. Qc1 Qd4+ 32. Kh1 Bxc5 33. Nxf7 Qe3 {Draw agreed in Schaefer - Siefring, email, 2019, in the view of the possible repetition} 34. Qb2+ Qd4 35. Qc1 *

