 b4 {the pawns are frightening, it makes sense to simplify with the help of} a5 $1 24. bxa5 Rxc5 25. a6 Rcxb5 26. Bxb5 Rxb5 $11) 9... Rb8 10. Qd1 Bf5 $1 {A necessary precision.} ({One move later} 10... O-O $6 11. e3 Bf5 {will be met by} 12. Bd3 $16) 11. Qa4 $5 (11. a3 {stops the intended jump at the cost of weakening the b3-square.} O-O 12. e3 (12. Qa4 Qd6 (12... Bd7 $5 13. Qd1 Be6 $44) 13. e3 e5 14. Bb5 exd4 15. exd4 {was Ivanisevic - Ivic, chess.com INT, 2021, Black has typical compensation after} Rfe8+ 16. Be3 Ng4 17. O-O Nxe3 18. fxe3 Bd7 $44) 12... e5 $1 {Indeed, Black should strive at opening the position: trading some pieces by} 13. Nxe5 {makes sense -} (13. Be2 $6 exd4 14. exd4 Ne4 15. O-O Nxd4 16. Nxd4 Bxd4 17. Nxe4 Bxe4 18. Bf3 {took place in Lenic - Gupta, Chess.com INT, 2017, Black missed the tricky intermediate move} Bd3 $1 19. Be2 $140 Bf5 $17 {[%csl Rb2,Gd4]}) (13. d5 $2 {is running into} Na5 $1 14. b4 e4 $1 15. Nd4 Nxd5 16. Nxd5 Qxd5 $15) (13. dxe5 Nd7 14. Be2 (14. e4 Be6) 14... Nc5 15. O-O Qxd1 16. Bxd1 Bd3 17. Be2 Nb3 18. Ra2 Nxe5 19. Nxe5 Bxe2 20. Nxe2 Bxe5 $11) 13... Nxe5 14. dxe5 Ne4 $1 (14... Nd7 $6 15. f4) (14... Qxd1+ $6 15. Nxd1) 15. Qxd8 (15. Nxe4 Qxd1+ 16. Kxd1 Bxe4 17. f4 Rfd8+ 18. Ke1 {transposes to the main line}) (15. Qd4 Nxc3 16. Qxc3 Qd5 17. f4 Be6 {[%cal Gb8b3]} 18. b4 f6 $132) 15... Rfxd8 {The disappearance of the queens does not slow down Black's initiative:} 16. Nxe4 (16. f4 Nxc3 17. bxc3 Be4 (17... Rb3 18. Be2 Rxc3 19. Kf2 Rc2 20. Kf3 Bd7 $44) 18. Kf2 f6 19. Bc4+ Kf8 $44) 16... Bxe4 17. f4 ({with all the pieces still on their initial squares it is not surprising that the expansion} 17. f3 Bd5 18. e4 Be6 19. f4 {has brought little to White after} Rd4 20. Kf2 Rxe4 21. b4 c5 $1 $132 22. Bd3 $140 Rd4 $11 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Gc5b4] Steingrimsson - Djukic, Batumi, 2018}) 17... f6 ({we have already seen this blow at White's chain in the note from above, but fixing the future target on b2 by} 17... a5 $5 {at first is reasonable either}) 18. Bc4+ Kh8 19. exf6 (19. e6 f5 20. Rf1 (20. Ra2 Bb1 21. Ra1 Be4 $11) (20. Kf2 Bf6 $44 {[%csl Rc1]}) 20... Bxb2 21. Bxb2+ Rxb2 22. Rf2 Rxf2 23. Kxf2 Kg7 {is the critical position - it is not a rare phenomenon these days when the verdict of an opening line is determined in a deep endgame. The extra e6-pawn seems to be of little significance, as witnessed by the following variations:} 24. e7 (24. g3 Kf6 25. Ke2 Rd6 26. Rc1 Rc6 27. Kd2 Ke7 28. Bb3 Rxc1 29. Kxc1 Bb7 30. Kd2 Bc8 31. Kc3 Bxe6 $11) (24. Rc1 Kf6 25. Be2 c6 26. Bf3 Rd2+ 27. Kg3 (27. Ke1 Rd3 $11) 27... Bd5 28. Bxd5 cxd5 29. Rc7 Rd3 30. Kf2 Rxa3 $11) 24... Re8 25. Rc1 Rxe7 26. Be2 Kf6 27. Bf3 Bxf3 28. gxf3 Ke6 29. e4 Kd7 30. Rd1+ Ke8 $11) (19. O-O fxe5 20. b4 {is typically met by} c5 21. b5 exf4 22. Ra2 fxe3 23. Bxe3 {and} Bd3 $1 {is the ultimate equalizer -} 24. Bxd3 Rxd3 25. Bxc5 Rxb5 $11) ({similar is the picture after} 19. b3 fxe5 20. Ra2 exf4 21. exf4 Bd3 $1 $11) 19... Bxf6 20. O-O (20. Ra2 Bb1 21. Ra1 Be4 $11) (20. Ke2 Bxg2 21. Rg1 Be4 $11) (20. Kf2 c5 21. Re1 h5 $44 {[%csl Rb2,Rc1,Ge4,Gf6]} 22. Re2 Rd1 23. Re1 Rdd8 $11) 20... Bxb2 ({the patient approach} 20... c5 $5 21. g4 a5 {deserves serious attention, for instance} 22. g5 Bg7 23. Kf2 a4 24. Kg3 h5 $44) 21. Bxb2+ (21. Ra2 Bc3 22. a4 Rb4 23. Be2 {was drawn 5 moves later in J. Cuenca Jimenez - R. Pereira, Ovar, 2022, an interesting sample line is} c5 $1 24. Ba3 Rxa4 25. Bb2 Rxa2 26. Bxc3+ Kg8 27. Bc4+ Bd5 28. Bxa2 Bxa2 29. Ra1 Bc4 30. Rxa7 Rd3 31. Be5 Bd5 $1 $132 {/=}) 21... Rxb2 22. Rf2 Rxf2 23. Kxf2 Rd2+ 24. Be2 Bxg2 {came to the same result in Pranav - Mikhalevski, Budapest, 2019, possible is} 25. Ke1 Rb2 26. Rc1 Ra2 27. Rxc7 Rxa3 $11) (11. e3 $2 Nb4 $1 $19) 11... Qd7 ({But not} 11... Bd7 $2 12. e4 O-O 13. Bb5 $16) 12. a3 (12. e3 $2 Nb4 {once again spells danger for White -} 13. Qxd7+ Nxd7 14. Kd2 c5 $17 {Korley - Corrales Jimenez, Charlotte, 2021.}) 12... Be6 $1 {One more concrete and strong move - having exposed the b3-square Black is going straight for it. The alternatives are inferior:} (12... O-O 13. e3 Nd5 14. Bb5 Rb6 15. Bd2 a6 16. Bxc6 Rxc6 17. O-O $14) (12... Ne4 13. e3 $14) 13. e4 $146 {A worthy try.} (13. e3 Bb3 14. Qa6 O-O {is double-edged, e. g.} 15. Be2 (15. Qd3 {transposes to 13.Qd1, see below}) (15. Nd2 Bc2 16. Qc4 Na5 17. Qa6 Nc6 {may end in a repetition}) 15... Rfd8 $146 {A logical idea - the last piece is joining the game, and the rook is ready to reinforce either of the central breaks, as demonstrated by:} 16. O-O (16. Nd2 Rb6 (16... Bc2 $5) 17. Qd3 Na5 18. O-O e5 $11) 16... Rb6 17. Qd3 e5 18. Bd1 exd4 19. exd4 Na5 20. Ne2 (20. Re1 c5) 20... c5 21. Bd2 Bxd1 22. Raxd1 Nc6 $11) (13. Qd1 {took place in Yilmaz - Adhiban, Sharjah, 2021. Black can use the same strategy -} Bb3 14. Qd3 O-O 15. e3 Rfd8 16. Nd2 $140 e5 17. Nxb3 Rxb3 18. dxe5 Nxe5 19. Qxd7 Nfxd7 $44 {[%csl Gb3][%cal Gd7c5,Gg7a1] with huge play for the missing pawn}) (13. b4 Nd5 14. Bb2 Nxd4 (14... O-O $5 {is a reasonable idea to exert more pressure in advance}) 15. Qxd7+ Bxd7 16. Nxd4 Bxd4 17. O-O-O Nxc3 $1 18. Rxd4 Na4 $1 19. Rxd7 Kxd7 20. Bxh8 Rxh8 21. e3 Rb8 22. Bc4 c5 $11) 13... Bb3 14. Qa6 O-O $5 {A vigorous continuation in the spirit of the position.} (14... Nxd4 15. Nxd4 Qxd4 16. Be3 ({perhaps White should prefer} 16. Bb5+ Nd7 17. Be3 Qd6 $14 {and wait for a proper moment for capturing the a7-pawn}) 16... Qd6 17. Bxa7 Ra8 18. Bb5+ (18. Qxd6 exd6 19. Bb5+ Nd7 20. Be3 Bxc3+ 21. bxc3 Ba4 22. Bd3 Ke7 $44) (18. Qb5+ c6 19. Qxb3 Rxa7 20. Rd1 Qc7 21. Bc4 O-O 22. O-O Ne8 $44 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Ge8d6,Gf8b8,Gg7b2]}) 18... Nd7 19. Bxd7+ ({it is essential that} 19. Qb7 O-O 20. Bxd7 {is strongly countered by} Bc4 $1 {, when White has to give the piece back and reconcile himself with} 21. Bb5 Bxc3+ 22. bxc3 Bxb5 23. Qxb5 Rxa7 24. O-O Rfa8 $11) 19... Qxd7 20. Qb7 O-O 21. Qxb3 Rxa7 22. O-O c5 $44 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Gg7b2] with a nice version of the Benko.}) 15. d5 {The acid test for Black's opening play.} (15. Bb5 {is also demanding and forces Black to come up with} Rb6 16. Bxc6 Qxc6 17. Qe2 {and now the subtle} Nd7 $1 (17... Bc4 $2 {at once is running into} 18. Ne5) 18. Be3 Bc4 $1 19. Qc2 Rfb8 $44 20. b4 (20. Na4 Ra6 21. Nc3 Rab6 $11) 20... a5 $1 21. Na2 (21. Rc1 axb4 22. Na4 Ra6 $11) 21... Bb5 $5 {A curious attempt at complicating suddenly the course of the game, Black could simply regain the pawn with a level endgame.} 22. Qxc6 Rxc6 23. bxa5 Rc2 24. Nb4 Re2+ 25. Kd1 Nc5 $44) ({In reply to} 15. Be2 {the capture} Nxd4 16. Nxd4 Qxd4 {is more justified, Black has nothing to complain after} 17. Be3 Qd6 18. Qxd6 exd6 19. Bxa7 Rb7 20. Bd4 c5 $11) 15... Nxe4 $3 {A proper reaction to the challenge!} 16. Nxe4 Bxd5 ({Definitely not} 16... Qxd5 $2 17. Qd3 $16) 17. Qd3 ({Decentralizing the knight with} 17. Nc5 Qd6 18. Na4 {can hardly disturb Black, for example} Bxf3 19. gxf3 Qd5 $44 20. Be2 $140 Nd4 21. O-O Nxf3+ 22. Bxf3 Qxf3 23. Qc4 (23. Re1 Qg4+ $11) 23... Rbd8 24. Be3 Rd4 25. Bxd4 Qg4+ $11) 17... Qe6 $1 18. Nfg5 (18. Nfd2 $2 Nd4 19. Be2 Rfd8 $19) 18... Qe5 19. f4 Qd4 20. Qxd4 ({Or} 20. Nc3 Bxg2 $1 21. Qxd4 Nxd4 22. Bxg2 Nc2+ 23. Kf2 Bd4+ 24. Kg3 Nxa1 {with mutual chances in this highly unbalanced position, e. g.} 25. Nd5 Rb3+ 26. Nf3 Nc2 27. Nxe7+ Kh8 28. Rd1 Bxb2 29. Bxb2+ Rxb2 30. Rd7 Ne3 31. Bh3 Rb3 $15 {/=/}) (20. Bd2 $143 $6 h6) 20... Nxd4 21. Bd3 Nb3 22. Rb1 Nxc1 23. Rxc1 Rxb2 24. O-O Bd4+ 25. Kh1 c6 $1 {[%csl Gd4,Gd5] A picturesque situation!} 26. Nf3 {The bishops are so powerful, that White should better give up a pawn in order to coordinate his army.} (26. Rc2 $6 Rfb8) 26... Be3 27. Rcd1 Bxf4 $44 {With 3 pawns for the piece Black has equality at least.} *

