{[%evp 0,54,25,27,27,1,30,33,60,61,53,15,13,0,23,15,19,19,19,19,37,35,14,29,25,21,27,24,-21,-6,-12,-57,-22,10,28,35,35,43,47,25,15,21,17,10,7,11,-6,0,19,0,0,0,0,0,0,0,0]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. g3 {This is probably the only interesting deviation, even though White is usually opting for it with the queenside knight being still on its initial square and therefore more possibilities.} (5. Qa4+ Nc6 6. Nf3 {transposes to Chapter 16.}) (5. Qb3 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Nf3 c5 8. e3 {transposes to Chapter 3.}) 5... Bg7 6. Bg2 Nxc3 7. bxc3 c5 8. Nf3 ({Instead, the immediate} 8. e3 {[%cal Gg1e2] has the idea to establish the knight on the e2-square and leave the big diagonal free for the g2-bishop. Black has the adequate reaction} Qa5 $5 (8... O-O 9. Ne2 Nd7 10. O-O Rb8 $11) 9. Ne2 (9. Bd2 {keeps the option of taking with the c-pawn, then} O-O 10. Ne2 Nc6 11. O-O Qa6 {is pointing at the vulnerability of the light squares and c4 in particular -} 12. Nf4 Bd7 $132) 9... cxd4 {This capture, just before opponent's castling, must have been Black's idea. He can expect to exploit the pair of hanging central pawns in the next stages of the game.} 10. exd4 O-O 11. O-O Nc6 12. Qb3 Rd8 13. d5 (13. Be3 Bd7 14. Nf4 Rac8 $11) 13... Ne5 14. Bg5 (14. Nd4 Bd7 $11 {may just transpose}) 14... Re8 15. Nd4 Bd7 16. Rab1 b6 $11 {[%cal Ga8c8] K. Georgiev - V. Kramnik, Belgrade, 1997}) 8... Nc6 9. O-O {This move is leading to mass simplifications.} (9. e3 {is solid -} O-O 10. O-O Qa5 (10... Qc7) (10... Be6) 11. Bb2 (11. Qb3 b6) 11... Rd8 12. Nd2 Be6 13. Nb3 Qb5 $1 14. Rb1 {with a balanced game -} cxd4 15. cxd4 Bd5 16. Bxd5 Qxd5 17. Qe2 e6 18. Rfd1 b6 19. e4 Qd6 20. Rbc1 Rac8 $11) ({White's playing compensation after} 9. d5 $6 Bxc3+ 10. Bd2 Bxa1 11. Qxa1 Nd4 12. Nxd4 cxd4 13. Qxd4 {is arguable, e. g.} O-O 14. O-O Re8 $15 {[%cal Ge7e5]}) (9. Be3 {looks bizarre, Black should obtain a satisfactory position by simple means -} O-O 10. O-O cxd4 11. Nxd4 (11. cxd4 Be6 $11 {[%cal Ge6d5]}) 11... Na5 $5 (11... Bd7 12. Nxc6 Bxc6 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14. Qa4 Bxc3 15. Rac1 Qa5 16. Qxc6 Rac8 $11) 12. Qd3 (12. Rb1 Nc4 13. Qd3 Nxe3 14. Qxe3 {in Lazavik - Shomoev, Cheliabinsk, 2022, cannot seriously worry Black after, let us say} Qc7 $11) 12... a6 13. c4 (13. Rfd1 Qc7) 13... Qc7 14. Rac1 Bd7 15. Qa3 (15. Rfd1 Rad8) 15... Nxc4 16. Qxe7 Rae8 17. Qb4 b5 18. Bf4 Be5 19. Bxe5 Qxe5 $11 {C. Li - A. Giri, Doha, 2015.}) 9... cxd4 10. Nxd4 Nxd4 11. cxd4 Qxd4 (11... Bxd4 $143 $6 12. Rb1) 12. Rb1 O-O 13. Be3 (13. Bg5 Re8 $11) (13. Qxd4 Bxd4 14. Bh6 Rd8 15. Bxb7 Rb8 16. Bxc8 Rbxc8 $11 {Mamedyarov - Vachier Lagrave, Stavanger, 2019, is roughly equal either.}) 13... Qc4 $5 {Preserving the queens does not change the general verdict.} (13... Qxd1 14. Rfxd1 Be6 {, based on} 15. Rxb7 Rad8 $11 {is the simplest road to the draw, which is already practically unavoidable.}) 14. Bd5 (14. Qd2 Be6 15. Rfc1 (15. Rxb7 Rad8 $11) 15... Rad8 16. Qxd8 Rxd8 17. Rxc4 Bxc4 18. Bxa7 b5 19. Bc6 Bxa2 20. Rxb5 $11 {Shankland - So, Saint Louis, 2018}) 14... Qa6 15. Qb3 (15. Bc5 Bf6) 15... Qxe2 16. Bc5 (16. Rfe1 Qh5 $11) 16... Be6 17. Bxe6 Qxe6 18. Qxe6 fxe6 19. Rxb7 Rf5 20. Rc7 (20. Bxe7 Bd4 $11) (20. Bxa7 Ra5 $11) 20... Rd5 (20... Re8 $5 21. Bxa7 Be5 22. Rb7 Bd6 $11) 21. Bxe7 (21. Rb1 Be5 22. Rc6 Bf6 $11) 21... Rd2 22. a4 Bd4 23. Bg5 Ra2 24. Be3 Bxe3 25. fxe3 Rd8 26. Rxa7 {At this point a draw was agreed in Berkes - Grandelius, Legnica, 2021, in the view of the inevitable perpetual after} Rdd2 27. Rb1 Rg2+ $11 *

