{[%evp 0,26,13,20,28,13,37,40,54,45,45,45,45,31,28,19,19,23,24,29,27,32,20,16,19,12,19,11,27]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bd2 c5 $1 ({There is no reason to postpone this thematic blow. For instance, in case of} 6... O-O 7. e4 Nxc3 8. Bxc3 {the verdict of the position will depend on the same push, but then White can consider d4-d5, which is excluded by the leading move order.}) 7. Nxd5 {In connection with the next move - the only real try for an opening advantage. Black is very close to full equality after the central exchanges:} (7. Rc1 Nxc3 8. Bxc3 cxd4 $1 9. Nxd4 (9. Bxd4 O-O $11) 9... O-O 10. e3 e5 $5 (10... Bd7 $11 {[%cal Gb8c6]}) 11. Nf3 (11. Nb5 Nc6) 11... Qe7 $11) (7. e4 Nxc3 8. Bxc3 cxd4 9. Bxd4 O-O 10. Bxg7 Kxg7 $11 {is even easier for him.}) 7... Qxd5 8. Rc1 O-O (8... b6 $5) (8... Qxa2 $5 9. Rxc5 {can transpose, but there is} Na6 $5 {as well.}) 9. Rxc5 Qxa2 10. e3 {A pawn sacrifice for speedy mobilization of the kingside, which Black has to accept, as soon as the queen is not in real danger.} ({In case of} 10. Qc1 Nd7 $1 11. Ra5 Qe6 $15 {[%cal Gb7b6] Black is in a pole position for occupying the key c-file.}) 10... Qxb2 11. Bc4 {Now 12.Rb5 is a serious threat.} ({Less logical is} 11. Bd3 Nd7 12. Rb5 Qa2 13. Qc1 a6 14. Bc4 Qa4 15. Rb2 Nf6 $15) 11... Qb6 12. O-O {So far Korobov - Shahade, Chess.com INT, 2021. The position is strongly resembling the Gambit Variation, in which Black's queen uses a different route before snatching the a2-pawn. Here too, White will try to increase gradually pressure for the sacrificed pawn behind the shield of the central e3+d4 pair.} Qd8 ({Rc5 is a bit awkwardly placed and} 12... Nd7 {is another opportunity to emphasize its location and gain time for its development.}) 13. Qb3 e6 $15 *

