{[%evp 0,46,27,13,18,11,37,37,46,68,69,40,42,-3,-28,-21,-22,-22,-5,-7,-5,-34,52,34,41,43,62,56,62,62,95,32,27,-8,-22,0,0,21,17,0,31,31,0,23,34,34,40,40,39]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. cxd5 Nxd5 {Here the minor continuations on move 6 will be examined.} 6. Qa4+ ({The other queen sally} 6. Qb3 Nxc3 7. bxc3 c5 8. e3 O-O {transposes to Chapter 3.}) (6. Bg5 c5 7. Rc1 {is an interesting plan to mobilize the queenside out of the scope of the g7-bishop at first. Questioning the annoying bishop with} h6 $1 {is the best and now:} 8. Bh4 {moves the bishop away from the queenside and Black has a good reason to enter} (8. Bd2 {is leading us back to the restrained systems with ?c1-d2. Black has already succeeded in the thematic strike c7-c5 and is fine after} Nxc3 9. Bxc3 cxd4 10. Bxd4 (10. Nxd4 O-O 11. e3 Bd7 12. Be2 Nc6 $11) 10... O-O 11. Bxg7 Kxg7 12. Qxd8 Rxd8 13. e3 Be6 $1 (13... Nc6 14. Bb5 Bd7 $11 {Mamedyarov - Artemiev, lichess.org INT, 2020}) 14. a3 Bd5 15. Be2 Nd7 16. O-O Rac8 17. Rfd1 Nf6 $15) (8. Nxd5 $2 hxg5 $1 9. Rxc5 Na6 10. Rb5 Bd7 11. e3 Bxb5 12. Bxb5+ Kf8 $17) 8... Nc6 9. Nxd5 Qxd5 10. Rxc5 Qxa2 11. e3 (11. Qc1 $6 O-O 12. e3 Na5 $1 $17) 11... Qxb2 12. Bc4 (12. Bd3 {was countered with the concrete blow} e5 $5 13. O-O exd4 14. Qa4 Qb4 $1 15. Qxb4 Nxb4 16. Bb5+ Kf8 17. Nxd4 Bxd4 18. exd4 Kg7 $15 {in Van Wely - Fier, Germany, 2015}) 12... Qb4+ $1 13. Nd2 (13. Ke2 Bf5 $15) 13... O-O 14. O-O e5 $1 {A well-timed break for eliminating the proud d4-pawn, which can always enable White to retain long-term compensation. The latter cannot make use of the seemingly weakened f6-square, as witnessed by:} 15. Rb5 (15. Ne4 $6 Bf5 $1 16. Nf6+ (16. Nd6 exd4 17. Rxf5 Qxd6 $19) 16... Kh8 17. Nd5 Qa3 $17) (15. Qc2 exd4 16. Qxg6 ({an important finesse in favour of 7...h6! can be seen in} 16. Rb1 d3 $1 17. Qc1 Qa4 $17) 16... Qxc4 17. Qxg7+ Kxg7 18. Nxc4 Be6 $15) 15... Qa3 $1 {Once again this square is surprisingly safe for the queen!} 16. Qb1 (16. d5 Na5 17. Nb1 Qa1 $17) 16... Bf5 $1 17. e4 Bc8 $1 18. dxe5 (18. d5 Nd4 $17) 18... Nxe5 19. Bd5 Qd3 $1 {The easiest way to nip White's initiative into its bud, for example} 20. f4 (20. Qxd3 Nxd3 $15) 20... Qxd2 21. fxe5 Be6 $15) 6... Nc6 $1 ({The queen check can be justified by} 6... Bd7 7. Qa3 {with control over the c5-square.}) 7. e4 ({Perhaps White should better decline any complications with} 7. e3 O-O $11) 7... Nb6 8. Qc2 ({Clearly worse is} 8. Qb3 $6 Nxd4 9. Nxd4 Bxd4 10. Nb5 Be5 $17 {[%cal Gc8e6]}) 8... Nxd4 {The most natural continuation.} (8... Bxd4 $5 {is an alternative, but after} 9. Bb5 {Black seems forced to the retreat} Bg7 {, when he will have to cope with the opponent's initiative -} 10. Bf4 Bd7 $13) 9. Nxd4 Bxd4 $5 ({Riskier, though playable, is} 9... Qxd4 10. Nb5 Qb4+ 11. Bd2 Qxb2 12. Nxc7+ Kd8 13. Rc1 Qxc2 14. Rxc2 Rb8 15. Nb5 {, when Black should be careful -} Bd7 ({less adventurous is} 15... a6 16. Ba5 axb5 17. Bxb6+ Ke8 18. Bxb5+ Bd7 $11) 16. Nxa7 Ra8 (16... Nc8 $5 {is yet another shot at equality}) 17. Be3 Nc8 18. Nb5 Ra5 $11 {Jarmula - Licznerski, Krakow, 2019.}) 10. Bh6 (10. Nb5 $6 Be5 11. Bh6 c6 $15) 10... Bd7 $1 11. Rd1 e5 ({Less principled is} 11... c5 12. Nb5 Bf6 13. Qxc5 Rc8 $13 {[%cal Ga7a6,Gd8c7,Gc7c5] , even though the expected queenside expansion after, let us say 14.Qb4 a6 Qc7-c5 will probably leave the "centralized" position of the king without any dramatic consequences.}) 12. Nb5 ({A blunder is} 12. Ne2 $2 Bxf2+ $1) 12... Bxb5 13. Bxb5+ c6 $1 14. Bg7 Qd6 $1 {The neat point of Black's operation - the queen is going after ?b5, while the other bishop will need time to leave the corner.} 15. Bxh8 Qb4+ 16. Qd2 Qxb5 17. b3 f5 (17... O-O-O $6 18. Bf6 Rd7 19. Qc2 $14) (17... Rd8 $5 18. Bf6 Rd6 19. Bg5 f5 $44) 18. f4 $1 fxe4 19. Bxe5 Bc5 $5 ({Black can claim "just compensation" after} 19... Bxe5 20. fxe5 Nd5 21. e6 O-O-O $44) 20. Qc2 ({Riskier is} 20. Qe2 Qa5+ 21. Kf1 Nd5 {, regarding the rather precarious location of the king -} 22. Qxe4 O-O-O $44) 20... e3 21. Qe2 {Now, when the pawn has taken an essential square of the own knight, this move is more to the point.} ({Black's compensation after both} 21. Rd3 Nd5) ({and} 21. Qe4 Kf7 {is indisputable, as well as after the text move.}) 21... Qb4+ 22. Kf1 a5 23. h4 Nd5 $44 {Bittner - Schakel, ICCF email, 2014.} *

