{[%evp 0,48,27,13,27,5,33,37,68,38,40,4,29,19,13,10,38,32,45,30,29,36,23,-9,20,-2,19,-6,44,27,14,50,50,9,32,50,9,21,50,41,34,34,47,47,62,44,37,27,63,23,33]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Na4 {[%cal Ge2e4] An attractive idea to stop the thematic c7-c5, but the central pawn can be undermined from the other side as well, so} e5 $1 {is the principled reply.} 6. dxe5 (6. e4 Nb6 $132) 6... Nc6 $1 {Development at first! It is both more pleasant and strong to attack the e5-pawn in this way, for, as we are going to see, the f8-bishop has still good prospects on the f8-a3 diagonal.} 7. a3 {A prophylactic measure exactly against the possible bishop check. A look at the alternatives reveals that White should take care of it:} (7. Nf3 Bb4+ $1 8. Bd2 Qe7 9. a3 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 Nb6 $1 11. Nxb6 axb6 {similar is the picture after} 12. Qf4 ({harmless is} 12. e3 Nxe5 $11) ({in reply to} 12. Rc1 {Black can probably simply continue with his development, but there is also the direct} Nxe5 13. Qc3 Nxf3+ 14. gxf3 O-O 15. Qxc7 {The material advantage has been restored, but Black is much ahead in his mobilization.} Bd7 $5 (15... Qf6 $44) 16. Qxb6 Rac8 17. Rxc8 Rxc8 18. Qe3 Qf6 19. Bg2 {A necessity - the king should be evacuated as soon as possible.} Qxb2 20. O-O Bc6 $11 {[%cal Gc8e8]}) ({in case of} 12. Qc3 Bg4 $11 {the extra central pawn is not going to survive for long}) 12... O-O 13. g3 (13. e3 Ra5 14. Be2 Nxe5 $11) 13... Re8 14. Rd1 Ra5 $1 {and White has hardly anything better than} 15. Bg2 Nxe5 16. O-O Nxf3+ 17. Bxf3 Bh3 18. Rfe1 c6 $11) ({In reply to} 7. e4 $6 {Black is by no means obliged to retreat the knight as on the previous move. Instead, there are at least two promising continuations -} Bb4+ (7... Ndb4 8. Qxd8+ Nxd8 9. Ke2 Ne6 10. Nf3 Bg7 $15) 8. Bd2 Ne3 $1 9. fxe3 Qh4+ 10. g3 Bxd2+ 11. Qxd2 Qxe4 12. Bg2 Qxa4 13. Ne2 O-O 14. O-O Qb5 $15) 7... Nxe5 8. e4 Nb6 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. Nc3 ({A high-level game saw} 10. Bg5+ Be7 11. O-O-O+ (11. Rd1+ Bd7) 11... Ke8 12. Bxe7 ({to} 12. Bf4 {Black can even react with} f6) 12... Kxe7 13. Nc5 Nbd7 $11 {Vachier Lagrave - Caruana, Shamkir, 2015.}) 10... c6 $146 {Objectively this move is a novelty, though the idea to control the d5-square, thus restricting Nc3, is quite common.} 11. f4 {The most ambitious continuation, but the absence of the queens does not enhance White's temporary initiative.} (11. Bf4 Bg7 12. O-O-O+ Ke8 $11) 11... Nec4 12. Nf3 Bc5 $5 {Besides this sally, Black has solid options as} (12... Kc7) ({or} 12... Bg7) 13. Bd3 a5 14. b3 Ne3 15. h3 $5 {A clever attempt at trapping the brave knight, but Black has a worthy response.} Re8 $1 16. Ra2 Ned5 17. Ne2 (17. Rc2 Nxc3 18. Rxc3 Bf8 19. Kf2 Bg7 20. Rc2 Be6 21. Be3 Kc7 22. Rb1 Rad8 $11) 17... Ne3 $1 18. Nfd4 (18. Ng3 Nf5 $1 {can result in a very amusing repetition.}) 18... Nf5 ({Dubious is} 18... Nxg2+ $6 19. Kf2 Nh4 20. Rd1 $16 {[%csl Rh4]}) 19. Nxc6+ ({If White wants to win a pawn, then} 19. Nxf5 gxf5 20. exf5 {is the minor alternative in the view of} Nd5 {with plenty of activity, while the white king, being stuck in the centre, is a big concern for the first player -} 21. g4 Kc7 22. Rf1 b5 $44) (19. Nf3 Ne3 $11) 19... bxc6 20. Rc2 ({After} 20. exf5 Bxf5 21. Bxf5 gxf5 22. Rc2 Nd7 23. Rf1 Kc7 24. Rf3 Bb6 25. Bb2 Re6 $132 {/= Black's active pieces are at least compensating the defects in his structure.}) 20... Nd7 21. exf5 Bb6 $1 {The key to counterplay - the annoying Nd7-c5 is in the air.} 22. Rxc6 Bb7 {Even stronger than playing for trapping Rc6 with the help of 22...Bc5.} 23. Rc3 Rc8 {Yet another evidence of the principle, claiming that the threat is more dangerous than its execution. Indeed, Black can consider the capture of the g2-pawn, but the surprising insertion of the text move is adding more tension by resuming the jump to the c5-square.} 24. Rxc8+ Kxc8 $44 *

