{[%evp 0,40,32,13,18,11,33,44,46,40,42,58,51,17,-33,-38,25,34,57,7,13,-26,-6,5,-4,-4,-4,-4,4,0,18,38,23,39,53,45,37,39,5,-26,-5,25,15]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Na4 {This is probably a better version of 5.Na4. Nevertheless, such an extended approach is overoptimistic.} Bf5 $1 {A logical reaction. In his turn, Black is preventing the e3-e4 push.} ({A playable, but slightly passive option is} 6... O-O 7. e4 Nb6) 7. Nh4 ({The extravagant idea} 7. Nc5 $6 b6 8. e4 {does not bring any dividends after the simple} bxc5 9. exf5 cxd4 10. Nxd4 O-O $15) 7... Bd7 {A calm and reasonable reply.} ({The vigorous} 7... Nc6 $5 {contains certain strategical risk, but Black can rely on his central preponderance after} 8. Nxf5 gxf5 9. e3 e5 10. dxe5 Nxe5 11. Be2 Qd6 $11) 8. e4 {An invitation for a fight in the centre, which Black will gladly accept.} (8. Nc5 $6 {can once again hardly inspire, this time because of} e5 $1) ({An early repetition like} 8. Nf3 Bf5 $11 {is not illogical.}) 8... e5 $1 9. Nf3 exd4 $1 10. exd5 O-O $1 {A subtle and consistent move, especially when the targetted Na4 has nowhere to go in the view of the intended 11...Qe8.} ({Alternatively,} 10... Qe7+ 11. Be2 Qb4+ 12. Bd2 Qxa4 {regains the piece at once, but the initiative passes to the opponent after} 13. Rc1 $1) 11. Be2 (11. Nxd4 $2 Qh4 {[%csl Ra4,Rd4]} 12. Nf3 Qxa4 13. Qxa4 Bxa4 $19 {[%csl Rb2,Rd5,Re1]}) 11... d3 $1 {The point of the whole operation, which has started with 8....e5!} 12. Qxd3 ({Black does not experience any difficulties after} 12. Bxd3 Qe8+ 13. Be3 Bxa4 14. Qd2 Nd7 (14... Qd7 15. Be2 Bb5 $11) 15. O-O Ne5 16. Nxe5 Qxe5 $11 {either.}) 12... Bxa4 13. O-O c6 14. Qe4 Qe8 (14... Re8 $5 {is tempting but after} 15. Qxa4 Rxe2 {White has the powerful} 16. Bg5 $1 Qd7 17. Rae1 $1 {, when} Rxe1 18. Rxe1 {is forced. However, Black should hold in the ensuing endgame after} Na6 19. dxc6 Qxc6 20. Qxc6 bxc6 21. b3 Nb4 $11) 15. Qxa4 Qxe2 16. d6 $5 ({The demanding} 16. Qb3 {is typically countered with} Na6 {and Black seems fine -} 17. Be3 (17. d6 Nc5 $132) (17. Qxb7 {is effectively met by the same} Nc5 {with ample compensation}) 17... Qxb2 18. Qxb2 Bxb2 19. Rab1 Ba3 20. Rxb7 cxd5 21. Rd1 Nc5 22. Rc7 Ne6 $11 {Li Chao2 - Nepomniachtchi, Moscow, 2016.}) 16... Nd7 {[%csl Gd7]} 17. Re1 ({Here} 17. Bg5 {is well-answered with} Nb6 18. Qa5 Nd5 19. Rad1 $140 Qxb2 20. Rb1 Qc3 21. Qxc3 Bxc3 22. Rxb7 f6 23. Bd2 Rf7 $11 {The mighty Nd5 disables the passed d6-pawn, as neither of White's rooks can support it.}) 17... Nb6 $1 18. Qh4 Qc4 19. Bf4 Nd5 ({This planting of the knight at a perfect position can also be preceded by} 19... h5 $5 {in order to avoid the little tactical trick on the next move.}) 20. Re4 $5 Qd3 $132 ({Of course not} 20... Qxe4 $2 21. Ng5 $18) *

